# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: sheep
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:sheep/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] The **10th edition of *Systema Naturae*** (Latin; the English title is *A General System of Nature*) is a book written by Swedish naturalist Carl Linnaeus and published in two volumes in 1758 and 1759, which marks the starting point of zoological nomenclature.
[src:sheep/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] In it, Linnaeus introduced binomial nomenclature for animals, something he had already done for plants in his 1753 publication of *Species Plantarum*.
[src:sheep/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] Before 1758, most biological catalogues had used polynomial names for the taxa included, including earlier editions of *Systema Naturae*.
[src:sheep/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] The first work to consistently apply binomial nomenclature across the animal kingdom was the 10th edition of *Systema Naturae*.
[src:sheep/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] The International Commission on Zoological Nomenclature therefore chose 1 January 1758 as the "starting point" for zoological nomenclature and asserted that the 10th edition of *Systema Naturae* was to be treated as if published on that date.
[src:sheep/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] Names published before that date are unavailable, even if they would otherwise satisfy the rules.
[src:sheep/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] The only work which takes priority over the 10th edition is Carl Alexander Clerck's **Svenska Spindlar** or **Aranei Suecici**, which was published in 1757, but is also to be treated as if published on January 1, 1758.
[src:sheep/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] During Linnaeus' lifetime, *Systema Naturae* was under continuous revision.
[src:sheep/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] Progress was incorporated into new and ever-expanding editions; for example, in his 1st edition (1735), whales and manatees were originally classified as species of fish (as was thought to be the case then).
[src:sheep/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] In the 10th edition, they were both moved into the mammal class.
[src:sheep/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] The animal kingdom, as described by Linnaeus: "Animals enjoy sensation by means of a living organization, animated by a medullary substance; perception by nerves; and motion by the exertion of the will.
[src:sheep/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] They have members for the different purposes of life; organs for their different senses; and faculties (or powers) for the application of their different perceptions.
[src:sheep/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] The list has been broken down into the original six classes Linnaeus described for animals: **Mammalia**, **Aves**, **Amphibia**, **Pisces**, **Insecta**, and **Vermes**.
[src:sheep/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] By current standards Pisces and Vermes are informal groupings, Insecta also contained arachnids and crustaceans, and one order of Amphibia comprised sharks, lampreys, and sturgeons.
[src:sheep/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] Linnaeus described mammals as: "Animals that suckle their young by means of lactiferous teats.
[src:sheep/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] In external and internal structure they resemble man: most of them are quadrupeds; and with man, their natural enemy, inhabit the surface of the Earth.
[src:sheep/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] Linnaeus described birds as: "A beautiful and cheerful portion of created nature consisting of animals having a body covered with feathers and down; protracted and naked jaws (the beak), two wings formed for flight, and two feet.
[src:sheep/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] Linnaeus described fish as: "Always inhabiting the waters; are swift in their motion and voracious in their appetites.
[src:sheep/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] They breathe by means of gills, which are generally united by a bony arch; swim by means of radiate fins, and are mostly covered over with cartilaginous scales.
[src:sheep/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] Linnaeus described his "Vermes" as: "Animals of slow motion, soft substance, able to increase their bulk and restore parts which have been destroyed, extremely tenacious of life, and the inhabitants of moist places.
[src:sheep/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] Many of them are without a distinct head, and most of them without feet.
[src:sheep/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] They are principally distinguished by their tentacles (or feelers).
[src:sheep/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] The second volume, published in 1759, detailed the kingdom Plantae, in which Linnaeus included true plants, as well as fungi, algae and lichens.
[src:sheep/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] In addition to repeating the species he had previously listed in his *Species Plantarum* (1753), and those published in the intervening period, Linnaeus described several hundred new plant species.
[src:sheep/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] The species from *Species Plantarum* were numbered sequentially, while the new species were labelled with letters.
[src:sheep/4-h] 4-H operates as a partnership between federal, state, and local authorities.
[src:sheep/4-h] Federal leadership is provided by the National Institute of Food and Agriculture (NIFA), an agency within the United States Department of Agriculture (USDA).
[src:sheep/4-h] State-level leadership is provided by each state's land-grant university.
[src:sheep/4-h] Local 4-H programs are facilitated through county-based Extension staff.
[src:sheep/4-h] The foundations of 4-H began in 1902 with the work of several people in different parts of the United States.
[src:sheep/4-h] The focal point of 4-H has been the idea of practical and hands-on learning, which came from the desire to make public school education more connected to rural life.
[src:sheep/4-h] Early programs incorporated both public and private resources.
[src:sheep/4-h] 4-H was founded with the purpose of instructing rural youth in improved farming and farm-homemaking practices.
[src:sheep/4-h] By the 1970s, it was broadening its goals to cover a full range of youth, including minorities, and a wide range of life experiences.
[src:sheep/4-h] During this time, researchers at experiment stations of the land-grant universities and USDA saw that adults in the farming community did not readily accept new agricultural discoveries.
[src:sheep/4-h] However, educators found that youth would experiment with these new ideas and then share their experiences and successes with the adults.
[src:sheep/4-h] As a result, rural youth programs became a way to introduce new agriculture technology to the adults.
[src:sheep/4-h] Historians do not credit one sole founder.
[src:sheep/4-h] Instances of work with rural boys and girls can be found all throughout the 19th century.
[src:sheep/4-h] In the spring of 1882, Delaware College announced a statewide corn contest for boys, in which each boy was to plant a quarter of an acre, according to instructions sent out from the college, and cash prizes, certificates, and subscriptions to the *American Agriculturist* were rewarded.
[src:sheep/4-h] In 1904, while working for the University of Wisconsin–Madison and trying to repeat what he had accomplished in Kewaunee County over a decade before but with different intentions, "Daddy" R.A.
[src:sheep/4-h] Burns, then Superintendent of Schools of Richland County, Wisconsin, to have the Richland County Boys and Girls organize and assist in a corn-project activity to help market and distribute improved seeds to the farmers in the state of Wisconsin (and beyond).
[src:sheep/4-h] Graham began one of the youth programs in Clark County, Ohio, in 1902, which is also considered one of the births of the 4-H program in the United States.
[src:sheep/4-h] The first club was called "The Tomato Club" or the "Corn Growing Club".
[src:sheep/4-h] "Dad" Erickson of Douglas County, Minnesota, started local agricultural after-school clubs and fairs also in 1902.
[src:sheep/4-h] Jessie Field Shambaugh developed the clover pin with an H on each leaf in 1910, and, by 1912, they were called 4-H clubs.
[src:sheep/4-h] Early 4-H programs in Colorado began with youth instruction offered by college agricultural agents as early as 1910, as part of the outreach mission of the Colorado land grant institutions.
[src:sheep/4-h] The Smith-Lever Act formalized the 4-H programs and clubs that began in the midwestern region of the United States.
[src:sheep/4-h] Although different activities were emphasized for boys and girls, 4-H was one of the first youth organizations to give equal attention to both genders (cf., erstwhile Boys Clubs of America).
[src:sheep/4-h] The first appearance of the term "4-H Club" in a federal document was in "Organization and Results of Boys' and Girls' Club Work," by Oscar Herman Benson (1875–1951) and Gertrude L.
[src:sheep/4-h] By 1924, the clubs were organized as 4-H clubs, and the clover emblem was adopted.
[src:sheep/4-h] Warren expanded the scope of girls' activities under the program (promoting garment making, room decorating, and hot lunches), and wrote extensive training materials.
[src:sheep/4-h] The first 4-H camp was held in Randolph County, West Virginia.
[src:sheep/4-h] Originally, these camps were for what was referred to as "Corn Clubs".
[src:sheep/4-h] Campers slept in corn fields in tents, only to wake up and work almost the entirety of each day.
[src:sheep/4-h] Adams began a boys' corn club in Newton County, Georgia, in 1904.
[src:sheep/4-h] 4-H membership hit an all-time high in 1974 as a result of its popular educational program about nutrition, *Mulligan Stew*, shown in schools and on television across the country.
[src:sheep/4-h] Today, 4-H clubs and activities are no longer focused primarily on agricultural activities, instead emphasizing personal growth and preparation for lifelong learning.
[src:sheep/4-h] Participation is greatest during the elementary school years, with enrollment in programs and activities peaking in the 4th grade.
[src:sheep/4-h] In the American South during the mid-1960s, 4-H began to broaden its programming to cover life experiences unrelated to agriculture.
[src:sheep/4-h] It merged its segregated African American and white programs, but full-fledged integration proved elusive.
[src:sheep/4-h] 4-H was successful in removing gender-based restrictions on participation.
[src:sheep/4-h] The organization is funded by the USDA and by state and local governments.
[src:sheep/4-h] The National 4-H Council's programs are also supported by a number of corporations including Google, Verizon, Microsoft, Land O'Lakes Inc., and Tractor Supply Co.
[src:sheep/4-h] Past Honorary Chairmen of Council have included U.S.
[src:sheep/4-h] Presidents Calvin Coolidge, Herbert Hoover, Franklin D.
[src:sheep/4-h] Roosevelt, Harry Truman, Dwight Eisenhower, John F.
[src:sheep/4-h] Johnson, Richard Nixon, Jimmy Carter, Ronald Reagan, George H.
[src:sheep/4-h] The 4-H Pledge articulates the organization’s values and goals for its members.
[src:sheep/4-h] 4-H members traditionally recite the pledge at club meetings and other 4-H events.
[src:sheep/4-h] The 4-H Pledge was adopted nationwide in 1927.
[src:sheep/4-h] It was written by Otis Hall, a state 4-H leader from Kansas.
[src:sheep/4-h] In 1973, the pledge was modified slightly when the phrase “and my world” was added to the final line.
[src:sheep/4-h] The official emblem of 4-H is a green four-leaf clover.
[src:sheep/4-h] There is a white H on each leaf to represent the four values of Head, Heart, Hands, and Health.
[src:sheep/4-h] The stem of the clover always points to the right.
[src:sheep/4-h] The emblem was initially designed in 1907 by O.
[src:sheep/4-h] Benson, the superintendent of Wright County Schools in Iowa.
[src:sheep/4-h] Some believe that Benson selected the four leaf clover because it represented the idea of “four-square education," an approach to education that emphasizes the balanced development of education, physical growth, moral character, and fellowship.
[src:sheep/4-h] The 4-H name and emblem were previously federally protected under federal code 18 U.S.C.
[src:sheep/4-h] 707, which was enacted in 1939 and amended in 1948.
[src:sheep/4-h] This act prohibited unauthorized use of the 4-H name or emblem, and entrusted the Secretary of Agriculture with its care and protection.
[src:sheep/4-h] This protection was a unique privilege shared by only a few national symbols such as the Presidential Seal and Smokey Bear.
[src:sheep/4-h] 707 was repealed under the Consolidated Appropriations Act of 2021.
[src:sheep/4-h] Title X of this Act, originally introduced as the Clean Up the Code Act of 2019, removed certain outdated provisions from the U.S. criminal code, including protection of the 4-H name and emblem.
[src:sheep/4-h] Through the program's tie to land-grant institutions of higher education, 4-H academic staff are responsible for advancing the field of youth development.
[src:sheep/4-h] Professional academic staff are committed to innovation, the creation of new knowledge, and the dissemination of new forms of program practice and research.
[src:sheep/4-h] Youth development research is undertaken in a variety of forms including program evaluation, applied research, and introduction of new programs.
[src:sheep/4-h] Over 500,000 volunteer leaders help to coordinate the 4-H program at the county level.
[src:sheep/4-h] Volunteers plan and conduct 4-H related activities, develop and maintain educational programs, or assist in fundraising.
[src:sheep/4-h] Activities include youth development programs, project groups, camps, conferences, or animal shows.
[src:sheep/4-h] The volunteers' goal is to help youth achieve greater self-confidence and self-responsibility, learn new skills, and build relationships.
[src:sheep/4-h] Volunteers are directed by 4-H's professional staff.
[src:sheep/4-h] 4-H Afterschool helps 4-H and other youth-serving organizations create and improve programs for students in communities across the U.S.
[src:sheep/4-h] 4-H Afterschool programs utilize experimental and cooperative learning activities and provide interaction with competent adults.
[src:sheep/4-h] Results of retrospective pre/post-surveys indicate that children enrolled in the program showed life skill gain over time, and that gains on specific life skills differed as a function of age, gender, and ethnicity.
[src:sheep/4-h] The life skills gained through 4-H Afterschool give children the tools they need for perceiving and responding to diverse life situations and achieving their personal goals.
[src:sheep/4-h] Participation in these quality programs which use experiential and cooperative learning have all been found to contribute to children's social development and academic success.
[src:sheep/4-h] Each state runs its own camping program.
[src:sheep/4-h] Believed to be the world's first 4-H camp was held in July 1915 on the Crouch family farm along the Tygart Valley River near Elkwater, West Virginia.
[src:sheep/4-h] The youth in attendance named the location Camp Good Luck.
[src:sheep/4-h] The first state 4-H camp was held at Jackson's Mill outside of Weston, West Virginia.
[src:sheep/4-h] 4-H camping programs in most states are run through land-grant institutions, such as Washington State University, which runs the Washington program, and Pennsylvania State University runs Pennsylvania's.
[src:sheep/4-h] The Georgia 4-H camping program has the largest youth center in the world, called Rock Eagle.
[src:sheep/4-h] On 8 July 2015, to mark the centennial of 4-H camping, youth from Randolph County, West Virginia traveled back to the original Camp Good Luck site for a special commemoration and campfire program.
[src:sheep/4-h] A stone marker honoring Camp Good Luck had been placed adjacent to US 219 near the site but was moved to a spot off of Bell Crouch Rd. for greater safety and accessibility through the efforts of Randolph County 4-H volunteers and the West Virginia Division of Highways.
[src:sheep/4-h] Some states offer programs for youths in grades K-2 called Cloverbuds, Cloverkids, 4-H Adventurers, Primary Members, or Mini 4-H to youth ages five to seven.
[src:sheep/4-h] These programs provide a non-competitive learning environment and provide an introduction to a 4-H club experience.
[src:sheep/4-h] Many colleges and universities have collegiate 4-H clubs.
[src:sheep/4-h] Usually members are students who are 4-H alumni and want to continue a connection to 4-H, but any interested students are welcome.
[src:sheep/4-h] Clubs provide service and support to their local and state 4-H programs, such as serving as judges and conducting training workshops.
[src:sheep/4-h] They are also a service and social group for campus students.
[src:sheep/4-h] The first collegiate 4-H club started in 1916 on the Oklahoma State University - Stillwater campus.
[src:sheep/4-h] Finding its roots in the early 4-H movement in West Virginia, the 4-H All-Star program strives to recognize and challenge 4-H members and volunteers.
[src:sheep/4-h] "Teepi" Kendrick sought to develop youth to "be yourself at your best" and to "make the best better" through a fourfold personal development pattern involving the head, hands, heart, and, at that time, hustle.
[src:sheep/4-h] It was with this philosophy, in collaboration with others, that the 4-H emblem was born.
[src:sheep/4-h] In an attempt to harbor further individual growth, Kendrick recognized excellence with pins bearing one, two, three, and four H's.
[src:sheep/4-h] Recognition for outstanding participation was rewarded from 1917 to 1921 with trips to a Prize Winner's Course at West Virginia University.
[src:sheep/4-h] Members who demonstrated outstanding qualities at these courses were awarded five-pointed red pins with five H's, with this additional *H* to symbolize honor.
[src:sheep/4-h] The recipients of these pins were referred to by Kendrick as "All Stars".
[src:sheep/4-h] It was following the pin consecration ceremony in 1919 that the official West Virginia 4-H All Stars organization was chartered, becoming the Alpha chapter of the nationwide 4-H honorary.
[src:sheep/4-h] The symbol of the All Stars is a red star enveloping a gemstone chip over the 4-H emblem.
[src:sheep/4-h] Each point of the star represents a pillar of character: "Beauty, Fortitude, Service, Truth, and Love".
[src:sheep/4-h] Many states have All Star programs, although All Star programs vary from state to state.
[src:sheep/4-h] Selection as a 4-H All Star is a recognition of achievement.
[src:sheep/4-h] In California for example, it is the highest achievement award at the county level and is a position awarded annually.
[src:sheep/4-h] Similarly, the capstone award in Texas 4-H is the Gold Star Award, which is given to Seniors who have shown outstanding leadership and proficiency in their project areas.
[src:sheep/4-h] In Virginia, on the other hand, All-Stars are not simply those who have achieved an All-Star award, but are those who have gained membership into the Virginia All-Stars organization.
[src:sheep/4-h] After reaching the age of 15, 4-H members are eligible to apply for membership into the All-Stars organization, which promotes the continuation of 4-H principles.
[src:sheep/4-h] Many conferences are held at various levels of the 4-H program for youth and adults.
[src:sheep/4-h] The National 4-H Conference, which was held at the National 4-H Youth Conference Center in Chevy Chase, Maryland, until it was sold in 2021, is the USDA Secretary's premier youth development opportunity to engage youth in developing recommendations for the 4-H Youth Development Program.
[src:sheep/4-h] The Conference still meets annually in and around Washington, DC.
[src:sheep/4-h] The National 4-H Conference is held in Arlington, VA.
[src:sheep/4-h] The National 4-H Congress is an annual educational conference that brings together 4-H delegates between the ages of 14 and 19 from across America to share cultural experiences and discuss important issues facing youth.
[src:sheep/4-h] This five-day event is typically held during the weekend of Thanksgiving and has been hosted in Atlanta, since 1998.
[src:sheep/4-h] Throughout the conference, 4-H delegates attend numerous workshops, participate in community service activities, and listen to speakers in an effort to develop compassion and increase social awareness.
[src:sheep/4-h] Citizenship Washington Focus is a week-long conference offered for high school-aged students.
[src:sheep/4-h] At the conference, students have the opportunity to learn how to be citizen leaders in their communities.
[src:sheep/4-h] Throughout the week in Washington, D.C., participants visit monuments, meet with members of Congress, and develop communication, leadership and citizenship skills.
[src:sheep/4-h] Other conferences are held by regional and state entities for youth, for volunteer development, or for professional development for staff.
[src:sheep/4-h] For many years, use of Native American names and certain themed activities was part of the summer camping programs of some eastern states.
[src:sheep/4-h] However, the practice was considered to be offensive and protests were raised.
[src:sheep/4-h] They also eliminated the practice of having children wear feather headdresses, and stopped having campers engage in "stereotypical motions and dances," including chanting "Ugh!
[src:sheep/4-h] However, the state program deemed the dividing of campers into groups, called "tribes" named after actual Indian Nations, to be respectful and acceptable.
[src:sheep/4-h] Although 4-H was first founded in the United States in the early 1900s, more than 80 countries have since established their own versions of 4-H programs to offer government-supported youth development programming.
[src:sheep/4-h] Over 48 countries use some variation of the 4-H Clover symbol to identify their youth development programs.
[src:sheep/4-h] 4-H's global expansion was supported by foreign and U.S. government officials who saw youth development as a strategy to improve agricultural productivity.
[src:sheep/4-h] Canada was among the first to create their own 4-H program in 1913, although some suggest that 4-H Canada was created as early as 1905.
[src:sheep/4-h] European nations like Sweden and England began implementing 4-H programs in 1918 and 1921 respectively.
[src:sheep/4-h] Programs continued to develop across the globe into the 1930s and 1940s, with 4-H Clubs appearing in Australia, Haiti, and Venezuela.
[src:sheep/4-h] In recent years, Iraq and Mongolia have developed their own 4-H programs and adopted the clover symbol.
[src:sheep/4-h] Some 4-H alumni credit the program with helping them in later life.
[src:sheep/4-h] The National 4-H Hall of Fame honors 4-H volunteers, extension professionals and staff employees, donors and others, according to a criterion of "significant impact on the 4-H program and/or 4-H members through the contribution of time, energy, financial resources, etc.".
[src:sheep/4-h] The hall of fame was established in 2002 by the National Association of Extension 4-H Youth Development Professionals (NAE4-HYDP).
[src:sheep/a-wild-sheep-chase] While the original story of *A Wild Sheep Chase* was set in the 1970s, translator Alfred Birnbaum and Kodansha editor Elmer Luke wanted a story that was more contemporary and also appealed to American readers.
[src:sheep/a-wild-sheep-chase] In the novel, Murakami blends elements of American and English literature with Japanese contexts, exploring post-WWII Japanese cultural identity.
[src:sheep/a-wild-sheep-chase] The book is part mystery and part magical realism with a postmodern twist.
[src:sheep/a-wild-sheep-chase] This quasi-detective tale follows an unnamed, chain-smoking narrator and his adventures in Tokyo and Hokkaido in 1978.
[src:sheep/a-wild-sheep-chase] The narrator fulfills the favor, in the process discovering that J's bar has moved from its former dingy basement into a modern building, and that the sea had been paved over for new development.
[src:sheep/a-wild-sheep-chase] Months later, the narrator's business partner is contacted by a mysterious man representing 'The Boss,' a central force behind Japan's political and economic elite, who is now slowly dying due to health issues.
[src:sheep/a-wild-sheep-chase] At his request, the narrator is driven to the Boss's estate in a limo, befriending the religious chauffeur along the way.
[src:sheep/a-wild-sheep-chase] At the estate, the Boss' secretary tells the narrator that his agency must immediately cease publication of the photo.
[src:sheep/a-wild-sheep-chase] He also explains that a strange sheep with a star-shaped birthmark, pictured in the advertisement, was in some way the secret source of the Boss' power and that he has one month to find that sheep or his career and life will be ruined.
[src:sheep/a-wild-sheep-chase] After some deliberation and preparation, the narrator and his girlfriend, who possesses magically seductive and supernaturally perceptive ears, decide to travel to the north of Japan to find the sheep and his vagabond friend.
[src:sheep/a-wild-sheep-chase] Throughout the novel, there is a dual storyline concerning the whereabouts of the Rat; who had been moving around the country, doing a variety of odd jobs and exploring whatever town that he had happened to travel to.
[src:sheep/a-wild-sheep-chase] The Rat held limited correspondence with the narrator through letters.
[src:sheep/a-wild-sheep-chase] After giving his elderly cat to the Boss' chauffeur to watch while he is gone, the narrator and his girlfriend fly to Sapporo to begin their hunt for the landscape and sheep in the photo.
[src:sheep/a-wild-sheep-chase] There the narrator's girlfriend digs through various texts in the library and they explore the city.
[src:sheep/a-wild-sheep-chase] The girlfriend's ears help to guide them to the Dolphin Hotel which is a shadow of its former self.
[src:sheep/a-wild-sheep-chase] It is run by a man who was once a sailor, but, due to an accident at sea, has only the use of one arm.
[src:sheep/a-wild-sheep-chase] The hotel owner points the pair to his father, the 'Sheep Professor', who is a bitter, eccentric man living upstairs in the hotel, still remembering the sheep from when he encountered them in Manchuria, decades before.
[src:sheep/a-wild-sheep-chase] The hotel owner and his father have a horrible relationship, and the Sheep Professor is reluctant, at first, to talk to anyone that his son brought, until the narrator mentions the sheep to the Sheep Professor.
[src:sheep/a-wild-sheep-chase] The Sheep Professor tells them of his encounter with the star-backed sheep and the obsession he still holds to find it again.
[src:sheep/a-wild-sheep-chase] It is the tip from the Sheep Professor that leads them to an isolated sheep farm, tended to by a man who is familiar with a man who matches the Rat's physical description and knows the trail to the pasture where the sheep are brought to graze each summer.
[src:sheep/a-wild-sheep-chase] With his help, the narrator and his girlfriend walk the trail that leads to the house.
[src:sheep/a-wild-sheep-chase] Inside there is nothing but antique furniture, dust, supplies and a barely used car in the garage.
[src:sheep/a-wild-sheep-chase] The narrator prepares to wait until the inhabitant of the house arrives, figuring that it would be the Rat or the sheep itself.
[src:sheep/a-wild-sheep-chase] While the narrator naps, his girlfriend makes a stew, which is done by the time the narrator awakes.
[src:sheep/a-wild-sheep-chase] However, his girlfriend abruptly leaves the house while he is asleep.
[src:sheep/a-wild-sheep-chase] The narrator is tempted to start back to town to look for her but quickly dismisses this.
[src:sheep/a-wild-sheep-chase] After over a week of waiting at the manor, the narrator runs out of smokes and decides to quit.
[src:sheep/a-wild-sheep-chase] He lives an isolated life of waiting, reading, cooking, morning jogs, and sipping whiskey waiting for the Rat, whom he correctly guesses to be the new host of the sheep.
[src:sheep/a-wild-sheep-chase] In this time, he encounters the Sheep Man, a peculiar four-foot character who seems to be a man dressed in a sheep costume.
[src:sheep/a-wild-sheep-chase] The Sheep Man asks for a drink and tells the narrator that his girlfriend is okay and was not harmed when she left.
[src:sheep/a-wild-sheep-chase] The narrator begs him to help to give a hint on the whereabouts of the Rat, to no avail.
[src:sheep/a-wild-sheep-chase] In darkness, the narrator encounters a familiar voice, the Rat's.
[src:sheep/a-wild-sheep-chase] Sharing a beer together, the Rat starts to answer the narrator's various questions.
[src:sheep/a-wild-sheep-chase] The house had belonged to his father, and had been a vacation home purchased from the US government for cheap, after they failed to turn the land into a radar station.
[src:sheep/a-wild-sheep-chase] They leased the land and sheep pastures to the town, and still do.
[src:sheep/a-wild-sheep-chase] The Rat, feeling nostalgia of happier times and feeling estranged from his family, encountered the sheep journeying back to the house, after hearing the Sheep Professor's story of the sheep and seemingly being drawn to the house.
[src:sheep/a-wild-sheep-chase] They say their final goodbyes, promising to see each other again.
[src:sheep/a-wild-sheep-chase] With the mystery solved and questions answered, the narrator walks away from the house.
[src:sheep/a-wild-sheep-chase] The Boss' assistant encounters the narrator and pays him a generous sum, telling him that his company has been dissolved as well.
[src:sheep/a-wild-sheep-chase] The Boss' representative allows the narrator to use his car and its driver to return to town.
[src:sheep/a-wild-sheep-chase] As the narrator returns to town, the driver informs him that his cat has grown fat and that the number to god's phone doesn't seem to work anymore.
[src:sheep/a-wild-sheep-chase] The narrator visits his old friend J's bar.
[src:sheep/a-wild-sheep-chase] He gives J the entire sum of the check from the Boss's assistant, therefore investing in the business with the condition of returns and that the Rat and he would always be welcomed with drinks in the establishment.
[src:sheep/a-wild-sheep-chase] Loose also argued that it has "markedly more narrative drive [than the previous two novels].
[src:sheep/a-wild-sheep-chase] Conversely, Foumiko Kometani stated in *Los Angeles Times* that the novel "evidences both his celebrated flair and his characteristic weaknesses".
[src:sheep/a-wild-sheep-chase] Murakami recalls that the editors of Gunzo, a Japanese literary magazine that had previously published his works, "didn't like *A Wild Sheep Chase* at all" because it was unorthodox for novels of the time.
[src:sheep/a-wild-sheep-chase] Popular reception, however, was positive and he credits this as his "real starting point" as a novelist.
[src:sheep/a-wild-sheep-chase] Today, *A Wild Sheep Chase* is often viewed as Murakami's first substantial work.
[src:sheep/a-wild-sheep-chase] Stretcher of *Publishers Weekly* selected it as his favorite book by the author, writing that Hokkaido is the setting of some of the "most interesting" parts of it.
[src:sheep/a-wild-sheep-chase] English professor Lowry Pei described the novel as the one in which Murakami "found the road he has been on ever since", due to tighter structuring and a protagonist who is more comfortable with expressing himself.
[src:sheep/a-wild-sheep-chase] In 2017, *Bustle*'s Melissa Ragsdale listed *A Wild Sheep Chase* as one of the five best Murakami books to start with, recommending it the most for readers who enjoy thrillers.
[src:sheep/a-wild-sheep-chase] The following year, Jeff Somers ranked it fourth among the novelist's books, arguing that "the sheer joy Murakami seems to take in telling [the story] shines through [...] by the end it deepens into a beautiful, deeply sad story of trauma and lost things.
[src:sheep/a-wild-sheep-chase] It's a breathtaking achievement, demonstrating the precise control Murakami has over tone and ideas".
[src:sheep/a-wild-sheep-chase] Keith Law wrote in 2011 that the novel was lesser than *The Wind-Up Bird Chronicle* and *Kafka on the Shore*, but he praised its plot.
[src:sheep/a-wild-sheep-chase] Law described the payoff as "a little underwhelming.
[src:sheep/a-wild-sheep-chase] This is the third book in Murakami's '"The Rat" Trilogy', preceded by *Hear the Wind Sing* and *Pinball, 1973*.
[src:sheep/a-wild-sheep-chase] All three books follow the sometimes surreal adventures of an unnamed first-person narrator and his friend, nicknamed 'The Rat'.
[src:sheep/a-wild-sheep-chase] All three novels begin from or refer back to November 25, 1970, the day on which Japanese author, poet, playwright and right-wing activist Yukio Mishima committed seppuku following a failed coup attempt at the headquarters of Japan's Self Defense Forces.
[src:sheep/a-wild-sheep-chase] Some Japanese critics have speculated that *A Wild Sheep Chase* is a rewriting or parody of Mishima's *The Adventure of Natsuko*.
[src:sheep/a-wild-sheep-chase] The sequel, *Dance, Dance, Dance*, continues the adventures of the unnamed protagonist.
[src:sheep/a-wild-sheep-chase] Locations and characters from *A Wild Sheep Chase* recur, most notably the Dolphin Hotel, the narrator's unnamed girlfriend, and the mysterious Sheep Man.
[src:sheep/a-wild-sheep-chase] In an article published by Manusya: Journal, the author claimed that the structure of the novel and lack of resolution creates a Labyrinth experience for the readers.
[src:sheep/a-wild-sheep-chase] The ending is open ended and allows for a cycle of various interpretations, similar to a labyrinth.
[src:sheep/a-wild-sheep-chase] Hokkaido has been interpreted alternately as the hero's inner mind and a mythological land of the dead.
[src:sheep/a-wild-sheep-chase] In a 2009 article for *The New Yorker*, Jon Michaud singled out one exchange in the 26th chapter for its multiple references to Herman Melville's *Moby-Dick*.
[src:sheep/abbott-s-duiker] Abbott's duikers stand around 65 cm (26 in) tall at the shoulder and weigh about 55 kg (121 lb).
[src:sheep/abbott-s-duiker] This duiker has a glossy, dark brown coat which is lighter on the underside.
[src:sheep/abbott-s-duiker] The face is paler and grey in colour, with a large red tuft on the forehead; the horns are thin and short (8 to 12 cm (3.1 to 4.7 in)).
[src:sheep/abbott-s-duiker] The secretive behaviour of Abbott's duiker, along with its largely nocturnal habits and preference for dense vegetation, means little is known about the ecology and behaviour of this species.
[src:sheep/abbott-s-duiker] It has been observed feeding on leaves in the forest understory, and on vegetation in forest clearings, and may feed on fruits, flowers and moss.
[src:sheep/abbott-s-duiker] An Abbott's duiker has also been seen with a frog in its mouth; duikers are known to capture and feed on live prey occasionally.
[src:sheep/abbott-s-duiker] The cryptic habits and alertness of Abbott's duiker unfortunately does not protect it entirely from predation.
[src:sheep/abbott-s-duiker] Young Abbott's duikers are probably preyed on by African crowned eagles (*Stephanoetus coronatus*) and pythons (*Python*species; *Python natalensis* and *Python sebae*), while duikers of all ages may fall victim to leopards (*Panthera pardus*).
[src:sheep/abbott-s-duiker] Abbott's duiker is endemic to Tanzania, in the Eastern Arc Mountains, Mount Kilimanjaro, and Southern Highlands in scattered populations.
[src:sheep/abbott-s-duiker] They live mainly in wet forests and swamps between 1,700 and 2,700 m above sea level, but can sometimes wander to much higher elevations at 4,000 m.
[src:sheep/abbott-s-duiker] They eat mainly fruit and possibly other plant matter.
[src:sheep/abbott-s-duiker] Abbott's duikers are nocturnal, spending the days at rest in thickets.
[src:sheep/abbott-s-duiker] They form regular pathways through the undergrowth, making them relatively easy to find.
[src:sheep/abbott-s-duiker] If threatened, they generally try to run, though they have been known to kill pursuing dogs when left with no escape route.
[src:sheep/abbott-s-duiker] Less than 1,500 Abbott's duiker are estimated to be left in the world, with no captive population.
[src:sheep/abbott-s-duiker] They are threatened by habitat destruction and poaching.
[src:sheep/abomasum] The **abomasum**, also known as the **maw**, **rennet-bag**, or **reed tripe**, is the fourth and final stomach compartment in ruminants.
[src:sheep/abomasum] It secretes rennet, which is used in cheese creation.
[src:sheep/abomasum] The word *abomasum* (*ab-* "away from" + *omasum* "intestine of an ox") is from Neo-Latin and it was first used in English in 1706.
[src:sheep/abomasum] It is possibly from the Gaulish language.
[src:sheep/abomasum] The abomasum's normal anatomical location is along the ventral midline.
[src:sheep/abomasum] It is a secretory stomach similar in anatomy and function to the monogastric stomach.
[src:sheep/abomasum] It serves primarily in the acid hydrolysis of microbial and dietary protein, preparing these protein sources for further digestion and absorption in the small intestine.
[src:sheep/abomasum] The abomasum is lined with glands to release hydrochloric acid and digestive enzymes needed to break down food.
[src:sheep/abomasum] It is very similar to the nonruminant stomach.
[src:sheep/abomasum] Dairy cattle on high production diets are susceptible to a number of pathologies, most commonly after calving.
[src:sheep/abomasum] A gas-filled abomasum can move into an abnormal location and become displaced.
[src:sheep/abomasum] If the abomasum displaces to the right, it is at risk of torsion.
[src:sheep/abomasum] A displaced abomasum will cause cows to present all or some of the following signs: loss of appetite, decrease rumen contractions, decrease cud-chewing, and drop in milk production.
[src:sheep/abomasum] While a displaced abomasum is not immediately life-threatening, veterinary care is required for surgical correction.
[src:sheep/abomasum] Milder cases can be corrected by rolling the cow over or forcing her to run up a steep hill.
[src:sheep/abomasum] Abomasitis is a relatively rare, but serious, disease of the abomasum whose causes are currently unknown.
[src:sheep/abomasum] The abomasum is used to make the *lampredotto*, a typical dish of Florence.
[src:sheep/abomasum] It is also fried and eaten with onions as part of the Korean dish *Makchang gui*.
[src:sheep/abomasum] Another dish made with the abomasum is the Persian Sirabi-Shirdan (borrowed in Turkey as *Şırdan*).
[src:sheep/abomasum] Chusta (literally abomasum) is a famous dish in Bihar, India.
[src:sheep/abomasum] In Japan, it is grilled and served as horumonyaki, this particular type of horumon is known as Akasen.
[src:sheep/abraham] The story of the life of Abraham, as told in the narrative of the Book of Genesis in the Hebrew Bible, revolves around the themes of blessing and promise, especially the promise of progeny and land.
[src:sheep/abraham] He is said to have been called by God to leave the house of his father Terah and settle in the land of Canaan, which God now promises to Abraham and his progeny.
[src:sheep/abraham] This promise is subsequently inherited by Isaac, Abraham's son by his wife Sarah, while Isaac's half-brother Ishmael is also promised that he will be the founder of a great nation.
[src:sheep/abraham] Abraham purchases a tomb (the Cave of the Patriarchs) at Hebron to be Sarah's grave, thus establishing his right to the land; and, in the second generation, his heir Isaac is married to a woman from his own kin to earn his parents' approval.
[src:sheep/abraham] Abraham later marries Keturah and has six more sons; but, on his death, when he is buried beside Sarah, it is Isaac who receives "all Abraham's goods" while the other sons receive only "gifts".
[src:sheep/abraham] Most scholars view the patriarchal age, along with the Exodus, as a late literary construct that does not relate to any particular historical era.
[src:sheep/abraham] Many scholars believe the Abraham traditions developed orally over centuries, before being incorporated into the Book of Genesis during the Persian period of Yehud, where they helped shape post-exilic Jewish identity and support competing claims to the land.
[src:sheep/abraham] The Abraham cycle (Genesis 11:27–Genesis 25:11) unfolds as a narrative of mounting tension, centered on the conflict between God's promise that Abram would father a lineage and become the ancestor of numerous nations, and a succession of crises that jeopardize this divine commitment.
[src:sheep/abraham] The storytelling method used here is the “obstacle story,” a literary device renowned for its enduring and universal popularity across cultures and eras.
[src:sheep/abraham] The Abraham cycle is not structured by a unified plot centered on a conflict and its resolution or a problem and its solution.
[src:sheep/abraham] The episodes are often only loosely linked, and the sequence is not always logical.
[src:sheep/abraham] The story portrays Abraham gradually assuming the role of the ideal religious person amid themes of blessing and promise, especially the promise of progeny and land.
[src:sheep/abraham] These themes form "narrative programs" set out in Genesis 11:27–31 concerning the sterility of Sarah and Genesis 12:1–3 in which Abraham is ordered to leave the land of his birth for the land God will show him.
[src:sheep/abraham] Terah, the ninth in descent from Noah, was the father of Abram, Nahor, Haran (Hebrew: הָרָן *Hārān*) and Sarah.
[src:sheep/abraham] Haran was the father of Lot, who was Abram's nephew; the family lived in Ur of the Chaldees.
[src:sheep/abraham] Haran died there while Terah was still alive.
[src:sheep/abraham] Abram married Sarah (Sarai) but, unlike Nahor and his wife Milcah, they were childless.
[src:sheep/abraham] Genesis 11 records that Terah, Abram, Sarai, and Lot departed for Canaan, but settled in a place named Haran (Hebrew: חָרָן *Ḥārān*), where Terah died at the age of 205.
[src:sheep/abraham] Then the narrative in Genesis 12 shows that God told Abram to leave his country and his kindred, and go to a land that God would show him, and promised to make of him a great nation, bless him, make his name great, bless them that bless him, and curse them who may curse him.
[src:sheep/abraham] Abram was 75 years old when he and Sarai left Haran with his nephew Lot, and their possessions and people that they had acquired, and they traveled to Shechem in Canaan.
[src:sheep/abraham] Abram built an altar to God in Shechem, and later he built another altar between Bethel and Ai.
[src:sheep/abraham] From there the party travelled to the Negev, or to the south.
[src:sheep/abraham] According to some exegetes, like Nahmanides, Abram was actually born in Haran and he later relocated to Ur, while some of his family remained in Haran.
[src:sheep/abraham] There was a severe famine in the land of Canaan, so that Abram, Lot, and their households traveled to Egypt.
[src:sheep/abraham] On the way Abram told Sarai to tell the Egyptians she was his sister, so that the Egyptians would not kill him.
[src:sheep/abraham] When they entered Egypt, the Pharaoh's officials praised Sarai's beauty to Pharaoh, and they took her into the palace and gave Abram goods in exchange.
[src:sheep/abraham] God afflicted Pharaoh and his household with plagues, which led Pharaoh to try to find out what was wrong.
[src:sheep/abraham] Upon discovering that Sarai was a married woman, Pharaoh demanded that Abram and Sarai leave, escorting them to the frontier.
[src:sheep/abraham] When they lived for a while in the Negev after being banished from Egypt and came back to the Bethel and Ai area, Abram's and Lot's sizable herds occupied the same pastures.
[src:sheep/abraham] This became a problem for the herdsmen, who were assigned to each family's cattle.
[src:sheep/abraham] The conflicts between herdsmen had become so troublesome that Abram suggested that Lot choose a separate area, either on the left hand or on the right hand, that there be no conflict between them.
[src:sheep/abraham] Lot decided to go eastward to the plain of Jordan, where the land was well watered everywhere as far as Zoara, and he dwelled in the cities of the plain toward Sodom.
[src:sheep/abraham] Abram went south to Hebron and settled in the plain of Mamre, where he built another altar to worship God.
[src:sheep/abraham] During the rebellion of the Jordan River cities, Sodom and Gomorrah, against Elam, Abram's nephew, Lot, was taken prisoner along with his entire household by the invading Elamite forces.
[src:sheep/abraham] The Elamite army came to collect the spoils of war, after having just defeated the king of Sodom's armies.
[src:sheep/abraham] Lot and his family, at the time, were settled on the outskirts of the Kingdom of Sodom which made them a visible target.
[src:sheep/abraham] One person who escaped capture came and told Abram what happened.
[src:sheep/abraham] Once Abram received this news, he immediately assembled 318 trained servants.
[src:sheep/abraham] Abram's force headed north in pursuit of the Elamite army, who were already worn down from the Battle of Siddim.
[src:sheep/abraham] When they caught up with them at Dan, Abram devised a battle plan by splitting his group into more than one unit, and launched a night raid.
[src:sheep/abraham] Not only were they able to free the captives, Abram's unit chased and slaughtered the Elamite King Chedorlaomer at Hobah, just north of Damascus.
[src:sheep/abraham] They freed Lot, as well as his household and possessions, and recovered all of the goods from Sodom that had been taken.
[src:sheep/abraham] Upon Abram's return, Sodom's king came out to meet with him in the Valley of Shaveh, the "king's dale".
[src:sheep/abraham] Also, Melchizedek king of Salem (Jerusalem), a priest of El Elyon, brought out bread and wine and blessed Abram and God.
[src:sheep/abraham] Abram then gave Melchizedek a tenth of everything.
[src:sheep/abraham] The king of Sodom then offered to let Abram keep all the possessions if he would merely return his people.
[src:sheep/abraham] Abram declined to accept anything other than the share to which his allies were entitled.
[src:sheep/abraham] Some time after these events, the voice of the LORD came to Abram in a vision, promising him a "reward", namely a son, and repeating the promise of the land and descendants as numerous as the stars.
[src:sheep/abraham] Abram was childless until then, and had anticipated that Eliezer of Damascus, head of his household, would inherit his estate on his death.
[src:sheep/abraham] He was to be rewarded in virtue of his trust in God.
[src:sheep/abraham] Abram and God then made a covenant ceremony, and God told Abram of the future bondage of his people "in a land that is not theirs", referring to Egypt.
[src:sheep/abraham] God then described to Abram the land that his offspring would claim: the land of the Kenites, Kenizzites, Kadmonites, Hittites, Perizzites, the Rephaim, Amorites, Canaanites, Girgashites, and Jebusites.
[src:sheep/abraham] Abram and Sarai tried to make sense of how he would become a progenitor of nations, because after 10 years of living in Canaan, no child had been born.
[src:sheep/abraham] Sarai then offered her Egyptian slave, Hagar, to Abram with the intention that she would bear him a son.
[src:sheep/abraham] After Hagar found she was pregnant, she began to despise her mistress, Sarai.
[src:sheep/abraham] Sarai responded by mistreating Hagar, and Hagar fled into the wilderness.
[src:sheep/abraham] An angel spoke with Hagar at the fountain on the way to Shur.
[src:sheep/abraham] He instructed her to return to Abram's camp and that her son would be "a wild ass of a man; his hand shall be against every man, and every man's hand against him; and he shall dwell in the face of all his brethren." She was told to call her son Ishmael.
[src:sheep/abraham] Hagar then called God who spoke to her "El-roi", ("Thou God seest me": KJV).
[src:sheep/abraham] From that day onward, the well was called Beer-lahai-roi, ("The well of him that liveth and seeth me": KJV margin), located between Kadesh and Bered.
[src:sheep/abraham] She then did as she was instructed by returning to her mistress in order to have her child.
[src:sheep/abraham] Abram was 86 years of age when Ishmael was born.
[src:sheep/abraham] Thirteen years later, when Abram was 99 years of age, God appeared to Abram again and called upon him to be "perfect" or "blameless", so that God could make a covenant with him.
[src:sheep/abraham] Abram fell or bowed to the ground in a gesture of reverence, and God gave Abram a new name: he was now to be called "Abraham".
[src:sheep/abraham] Abraham means "father of a multitude": he would be "a father of many nations".
[src:sheep/abraham] The new name denotes a new stage in Abraham's life.
[src:sheep/abraham] Abraham then received God's instructions concerning circumcision.
[src:sheep/abraham] God also declared Sarai's new name to be "Sarah", blessed her, and told Abraham, "I will give thee a son also of her".
[src:sheep/abraham] Immediately after Abraham's encounter with God, he had his entire household of men, including himself (age 99) and Ishmael (age 13), circumcised.
[src:sheep/abraham] Not long afterward, during the heat of the day, Abraham had been sitting at the entrance of his tent by the terebinths of Mamre.
[src:sheep/abraham] He looked up and saw three men in the presence of God.
[src:sheep/abraham] Then he ran and bowed to the ground to welcome them.
[src:sheep/abraham] Abraham then offered to wash their feet and fetch them a morsel of bread, to which they assented.
[src:sheep/abraham] Abraham rushed to Sarah's tent to order ash cakes made from choice flour, then he ordered a servant-boy to prepare a choice calf.
[src:sheep/abraham] When all was prepared, he set curds, milk and the calf before them, waiting on them, under a tree, as they ate.
[src:sheep/abraham] One of the visitors told Abraham that upon his return next year, Sarah would have a son.
[src:sheep/abraham] While at the tent entrance, Sarah overheard what was said and she laughed to herself about the prospect of having a child at their ages.
[src:sheep/abraham] The visitor inquired of Abraham why Sarah laughed at bearing a child at her age, as nothing is too hard for God.
[src:sheep/abraham] After eating, Abraham and the three visitors got up.
[src:sheep/abraham] Accompanied by Abraham, the visitors walked over to the peak that overlooked the "cities of the plain" to discuss the fate of Sodom and Gomorrah for their detestable sins that were so great, they moved God to action.
[src:sheep/abraham] Because of God's promise to Abraham regarding his destiny, God revealed plans to assess what these cities have done and confer judgment on them.
[src:sheep/abraham] At this point, the two other visitors left for Sodom.
[src:sheep/abraham] Then Abraham turned to God and pleaded decrementally with Him (from fifty persons to less) that "if there were at least ten righteous men found in the city, would not God spare the city?" For the sake of ten righteous people, God declared that he would not destroy the city.
[src:sheep/abraham] When the two visitors arrived in Sodom to conduct their report, they planned on staying in the city square.
[src:sheep/abraham] However, Abraham's nephew, Lot, met with them and strongly insisted that these two "men" stay at his house for the night.
[src:sheep/abraham] A rally of men stood outside of Lot's home and demanded that Lot bring out his guests so that they may "know" (v.
[src:sheep/abraham] However, Lot objected and offered his virgin daughters who had not "known" (v.
[src:sheep/abraham] They rejected that notion and sought to break down Lot's door to get to his male guests, thus confirming the wickedness of the city and portending their imminent destruction.
[src:sheep/abraham] Early the next morning, Abraham went to the place where he stood before God.
[src:sheep/abraham] He "looked out toward Sodom and Gomorrah" and saw what became of the cities of the plain, where not even "ten righteous" (v.
[src:sheep/abraham] Abraham moved to live between Kadesh and Shur, settling in Gerar, later associated with the Philistines".
[src:sheep/abraham] While he was living in there, Abraham openly claimed that Sarah was his sister, and she confirmed this assertion, leading King Abimelech to call for Sarah to be brought to him.
[src:sheep/abraham] God then came to Abimelech in a dream and declared that taking her would result in his death, because she was a man's wife.
[src:sheep/abraham] Abimelech had not laid hands on her, so he inquired if he would also slay a righteous nation, especially since Abraham and Sarah had claimed that they were siblings.
[src:sheep/abraham] In response, God told Abimelech that he did indeed have a blameless heart and that is why he continued to exist.
[src:sheep/abraham] However, should he not return the wife of Abraham back to him, God would surely destroy Abimelech and his entire household.
[src:sheep/abraham] Abimelech was informed that Abraham was a prophet who would pray for him.
[src:sheep/abraham] Early next morning, Abimelech informed his servants of his dream and approached Abraham inquiring as to why he had brought such great guilt upon his kingdom.
[src:sheep/abraham] Abraham stated that he thought there was no fear of God in that place, and that they might kill him for his wife.
[src:sheep/abraham] Further, Abimelech gave Abraham a thousand pieces of silver to serve as Sarah's vindication before all.
[src:sheep/abraham] Abraham then prayed for Abimelech and his household, since God had stricken the women with infertility because of the taking of Sarah.
[src:sheep/abraham] Two incidents follow in which Abraham and Abimelech resolve issues by agreement.
[src:sheep/abraham] Firstly, Abimelech, supported by Phicol, the chief of his troops, secures from the patriarch an agreement that he will act honestly in his dealings with Abimelech and his descendants, reciprocating the manner in which Abimelech says he has treated Abraham.
[src:sheep/abraham] Subsequently, a specific issue arises in relation to a well which Abraham has dug but which Abimelech's servants have taken over.
[src:sheep/abraham] Abimelech and Phicol approached Abraham because of a dispute over the well.
[src:sheep/abraham] Abraham reproached Abimelech due to his servants' aggressive attacks and the seizing of the well.
[src:sheep/abraham] Abimelech claimed ignorance of the incident.
[src:sheep/abraham] Then Abraham offered a pact by providing sheep and oxen to Abimelech.
[src:sheep/abraham] Further, to attest that Abraham was the one who had dug the well, he also gave Abimelech seven ewes for proof.
[src:sheep/abraham] Because of this sworn oath, they called the place of this well Beersheba.
[src:sheep/abraham] After Abimelech and Phicol headed back to Philistia, Abraham planted a tamarisk grove in Beersheba and called upon "the name of the LORD, the everlasting God".
[src:sheep/abraham] As had been prophesied at Mamre the previous year, Sarah became pregnant and bore a son to Abraham, on the first anniversary of the covenant of circumcision.
[src:sheep/abraham] Abraham was "an hundred years old" when his son, whom he named Isaac, was born, and he circumcised him when he was eight days old.
[src:sheep/abraham] During the celebration, however, Sarah found Ishmael mocking; an observation that would begin to clarify the birthright of Isaac.
[src:sheep/abraham] Ishmael was fourteen years old when Abraham's son Isaac was born to Sarah.
[src:sheep/abraham] When she found Ishmael teasing Isaac, Sarah told Abraham to send both Ishmael and Hagar away.
[src:sheep/abraham] She declared that Ishmael would not share in Isaac's inheritance.
[src:sheep/abraham] Abraham was greatly distressed by his wife's words and sought the advice of his God.
[src:sheep/abraham] God told Abraham not to be distressed but to do as his wife commanded.
[src:sheep/abraham] God reassured Abraham that "in Isaac shall seed be called to thee." He also said Ishmael would make a nation, "because he is thy seed".
[src:sheep/abraham] Early the next morning, Abraham brought Hagar and Ishmael out together.
[src:sheep/abraham] He gave her bread and water and sent them away.
[src:sheep/abraham] The two wandered in the wilderness of Beersheba until her bottle of water was completely consumed.
[src:sheep/abraham] In a moment of despair, she burst into tears.
[src:sheep/abraham] After God heard the boy's voice, an angel of the Lord confirmed to Hagar that he would become a great nation, and will be "living on his sword".
[src:sheep/abraham] A well of water then appeared so that it saved their lives.
[src:sheep/abraham] As the boy grew, he became a skilled archer living in the wilderness of Paran.
[src:sheep/abraham] Eventually his mother found a wife for Ishmael from her home country, the land of Egypt.
[src:sheep/abraham] At some point in Isaac's youth, Abraham was commanded by God to offer his son up as a sacrifice in the land of Moriah.
[src:sheep/abraham] The patriarch traveled three days until he came to the mount that God told him of.
[src:sheep/abraham] He then commanded the servants to remain while he and Isaac proceeded alone into the mount.
[src:sheep/abraham] Isaac carried the wood upon which he would be sacrificed.
[src:sheep/abraham] Along the way, Isaac asked his father where the animal for the burnt offering was, to which Abraham replied "God will provide himself a lamb for a burnt offering".
[src:sheep/abraham] Just as Abraham was about to sacrifice his son, he was interrupted by the angel of the Lord, and he saw behind him a "ram caught in a thicket by his horns", which he sacrificed instead of his son.
[src:sheep/abraham] The place was later named as Jehovah-jireh.
[src:sheep/abraham] For his obedience he received another promise of numerous descendants and abundant prosperity.
[src:sheep/abraham] After this event, Abraham went to Beersheba.
[src:sheep/abraham] Sarah died, and Abraham buried her in the Cave of the Patriarchs (the "cave of Machpelah"), near Hebron which he had purchased along with the adjoining field from Ephron the Hittite.
[src:sheep/abraham] After the death of Sarah, Abraham took another wife, a concubine named Keturah, and together they had six sons: Zimran, Jokshan, Medan, Midian, Ishbak, and Shuah.
[src:sheep/abraham] Abraham lived to see Isaac marry Rebekah, and to see the birth of his twin grandsons Jacob and Esau.
[src:sheep/abraham] He died at age 175, and was buried in the cave of Machpelah by his sons Isaac and Ishmael.
[src:sheep/abraham] In the early and middle 20th century, leading archaeologists such as William F.
[src:sheep/abraham] Ernest Wright and biblical scholars such as Albrecht Alt and John Bright believed that the patriarchs and matriarchs were either real individuals or believable composites of people who lived in the "patriarchal age", the 2nd millennium BCE.
[src:sheep/abraham] However, in the 1970s, new arguments concerning Israel's past and the biblical texts challenged these views; these arguments can be found in Thomas L.
[src:sheep/abraham] Thompson's *The Historicity of the Patriarchal Narratives* (1974), and John Van Seters' *Abraham in History and Tradition* (1975).
[src:sheep/abraham] Thompson, a literary scholar, based his argument on archaeology and ancient texts.
[src:sheep/abraham] His thesis centered on the lack of compelling evidence that the patriarchs lived in the 2nd millennium BCE, and noted how certain biblical texts reflected first millennium conditions and concerns.
[src:sheep/abraham] Van Seters examined the patriarchal stories and argued that their names, social milieu, and messages strongly suggested that they were Iron Age creations.
[src:sheep/abraham] Van Seters' and Thompson's works were a paradigm shift in biblical scholarship and archaeology, which gradually led scholars to no longer consider the patriarchal narratives as historical.
[src:sheep/abraham] Some conservative scholars attempted to defend the Patriarchal narratives in the following years, but this has not found acceptance among scholars.
[src:sheep/abraham] By the beginning of the 21st century, archaeologists had stopped trying to recover any context that would make Abraham, Isaac or Jacob credible historical figures.
[src:sheep/abraham] At some stage the oral traditions became part of the written tradition of the Pentateuch; a majority of scholars believe this stage belongs to the Persian period, roughly 520–320 BCE.
[src:sheep/abraham] The mechanisms by which this came about remain unknown, but there are currently at least two hypotheses.
[src:sheep/abraham] The completion of the Torah and its elevation to the centre of post-Exilic Judaism was as much or more about combining older texts as writing new ones – the final Pentateuch was based on existing traditions.
[src:sheep/abraham] The Book of Isaiah similarly testifies to tension between the people of Judah and the returning post-Exilic Jews (the "gôlâ"), stating that God is the father of Israel and that Israel's history begins with the Exodus and not with Abraham.
[src:sheep/abraham] According to Nissim Amzallag, the Book of Genesis portrays Abraham as having an Amorite origin, arguing that the patriarch's provenance from the region of Harran as described in Genesis 11:31 associates him with the territory of the Amorite homeland.
[src:sheep/abraham] He also notes parallels between the biblical narrative and the Amorite migration into the Southern Levant in the 2nd millennium BCE.
[src:sheep/abraham] Alan Millard argues that the name Abram is of Amorite origin and that it is attested in Mari as *ʾabī-rām*.
[src:sheep/abraham] He also suggests that the Patriarch's name corresponds to a form typical of the Middle Bronze Age and not of later periods.
[src:sheep/abraham] Some papers identify Abraham with the Amorite chieftain Abum, and his son Ishmael with Sumulael.
[src:sheep/abraham] The orientalist Mario Liverani has proposed to see in the name Abraham the eponymous ancestor of a 13th-century BCE tribe, the Raham, mentioned in a stele of Seti I found at Beth-Shean and dating back to around 1289 BCE.
[src:sheep/abraham] The tribe probably lived in the area surrounding or close to Beth-Shean, in Galilee (the stele in fact refers to battles that took place in the area).
[src:sheep/abraham] Liverani hypothesized that the members of the tribe of Raham called themselves "sons of Raham" (**Banu-Raham*), so that the name of their eponymous ancestor would have been "father of Raham" (**Abu-Raham*), that being the name of the patriarch Abraham.
[src:sheep/abraham] Finkelstein and Römer considered Abraham as ancestor who was worshiped in Hebron, with the oldest tradition of him possibly being about the altar he built in Hebron.
[src:sheep/abraham] Abraham is given a high position of respect in three major world faiths, Judaism, Christianity, and Islam.
[src:sheep/abraham] In Judaism, he is the founding father of the covenant, the special relationship between the Jewish people and God—leading to the belief that the Jews are the chosen people of God.
[src:sheep/abraham] In Christianity, Paul the Apostle taught that Abraham's faith in God, preceding receipt of the Mosaic law, made him the prototype of all believers, Jewish or gentile; and in Islam, he is seen as a link in the chain of prophets that begins with Adam and culminates in Muhammad.
[src:sheep/abraham] Specifically through Jacob, renamed "Israel" in Genesis 35:10, both "a nation and a company of nations" would arise, and the promise that his descendants would become a multitude of nations is maintained through Jacob's blessing of his grandson, Ephraim, in Genesis 48:19.
[src:sheep/abraham] In Jewish tradition, Abraham is called *Avraham Avinu* (אברהם אבינו), "our father Abraham", signifying that he is both the biological progenitor of the Jews and the father of Judaism, the first Jew.
[src:sheep/abraham] His story is read in the weekly Torah reading portions, predominantly in the parashot: Lech-Lecha (לֶךְ-לְךָ), Vayeira (וַיֵּרָא), Chayei Sarah (חַיֵּי שָׂרָה), and Toledot (תּוֹלְדֹת).
[src:sheep/abraham] Hanan bar Rava taught in Abba Arikha's name that Abraham's mother was named ʾĂmatlaʾy bat Karnebo.
[src:sheep/abraham] Hiyya bar Abba taught that Abraham worked in Teraḥ's idol shop in his youth.
[src:sheep/abraham] According to the *Legends of the Jews*, God created heaven and earth for the sake of the merits of Abraham.
[src:sheep/abraham] After the biblical flood, Abraham was the only one among the pious who solemnly swore never to forsake God, studied in the house of Noah and Shem to learn about the "Ways of God", and continued the line of High Priest from Noah and Shem, assigning the office to Levi and his seed forever.
[src:sheep/abraham] Before leaving his father's land, Abraham was miraculously saved from the fiery furnace of Nimrod following his brave action of breaking the idols of the Chaldeans into pieces.
[src:sheep/abraham] During his sojourning in Canaan, Abraham was accustomed to extend hospitality to travelers and strangers and taught how to praise God also knowledge of God to those who had received his kindness.
[src:sheep/abraham] Along with Isaac and Jacob, he is the one whose name would appear united with God, as God in Judaism is called *Elohei Avraham, Elohei Yitzchak, vEilohei Ya'akov* ("God of Abraham, God of Isaac, and God of Jacob").
[src:sheep/abraham] He was also mentioned as the father of thirty nations.
[src:sheep/abraham] In Mandaeism, Abraham (Classical Mandaic: ࡀࡁࡓࡀࡄࡉࡌ, romanized: *Abrahim*) is mentioned in Book 18 of the *Right Ginza* as the patriarch of the Jewish people.
[src:sheep/abraham] Mandaeans consider Abraham to have been originally a Mandaean priest, however they differ with Abraham and Jews regarding circumcision which they consider to be bodily mutilation and therefore forbidden.
[src:sheep/abraham] In Christianity, Abraham is revered as the prophet to whom God chose to reveal himself and with whom God initiated a covenant (cf.
[src:sheep/abraham] Paul the Apostle declared that all who believe in Jesus (Christians) are "included in the seed of Abraham and are inheritors of the promise made to Abraham".
[src:sheep/abraham] Throughout history, church leaders, following Paul, have emphasized Abraham as the spiritual father of all Christians.
[src:sheep/abraham] Augustine of Hippo declared that Christians are "children (or 'seed') of Abraham by faith", Ambrose stated that "by means of their faith Christians possess the promises made to Abraham", and Martin Luther recalled Abraham as "a paradigm of the man of faith".
[src:sheep/abraham] The Roman Catholic Church, the largest Christian denomination, calls Abraham "our father in Faith" in the Eucharistic prayer of the Roman Canon, recited during the Mass.
[src:sheep/abraham] In the introduction to his 15th-century translation of the Golden Legend's account of Abraham, William Caxton noted that this patriarch's life was read in church on Quinquagesima Sunday.
[src:sheep/abraham] He is the patron saint of those in the hospitality industry.
[src:sheep/abraham] The Eastern Orthodox Church commemorates him as the "Righteous Forefather Abraham", with two feast days in its liturgical calendar.
[src:sheep/abraham] The first time is on 9 October (for those churches which follow the traditional Julian Calendar, 9 October falls on 22 October of the modern Gregorian Calendar), where he is commemorated together with his nephew "Righteous Lot".
[src:sheep/abraham] The other is on the "Sunday of the Forefathers" (two Sundays before Christmas), when he is commemorated together with other ancestors of Jesus.
[src:sheep/abraham] Abraham is also mentioned in the Divine Liturgy of Basil the Great, just before the Anaphora, and Abraham and Sarah are invoked in the prayers said by the priest over a newly married couple.
[src:sheep/abraham] A popular hymn sung in many English-speaking Sunday Schools by children is known as "Father Abraham" and emphasizes the patriarch as the spiritual progenitor of Christians.
[src:sheep/abraham] Islam regards *ʾIbrāhīm* (Abraham) as a link in the chain of prophets that begins with Adam and culminates in Muhammad via *ʾIsmāʿīl* (Ishmael).
[src:sheep/abraham] Abraham is mentioned in 35 chapters of the Quran, more often than any other biblical personage apart from Moses.
[src:sheep/abraham] He is called both a *hanif* (monotheist) and *muslim* (one who submits), and Muslims regard him as a prophet and patriarch, the archetype of the perfect Muslim, and the revered reformer of the Kaaba in Mecca.
[src:sheep/abraham] Islamic tradition considers Abraham the first "pioneer of Islam" (which is also called *millat ʾIbrāhīm*, the 'religion of Abraham'), and that his purpose and mission throughout his life was to proclaim the oneness of God.
[src:sheep/abraham] In Islam, Abraham holds an exalted position among the major prophets and he is referred to as *Khalīlullāh*, meaning 'Friend of God'.
[src:sheep/abraham] Besides *Ishaq* and *Yaqub* (Isaac and Jacob), Abraham is among the most excellent and honorable men in the view of God.
[src:sheep/abraham] He is also mentioned in Quran as the "Father of Muslims", and is put forward as a role model for the community.
[src:sheep/abraham] The Druze regard Abraham as the third spokesman (*natiq*) after Adam and Noah, who helped transmit the foundational teachings of monotheism (*tawhid*) intended for the larger audience.
[src:sheep/abraham] He is also among the seven prophets who appeared in different periods of history according to the Druze faith.
[src:sheep/abraham] To ʻAbdu'l-Bahá, the Abraham was born to a family that was ignorant of the oneness of God.
[src:sheep/abraham] Abraham opposed his own people and government, and even his own kin, he rejected all their gods, and, alone and single-handed, he withstood a powerful nation.
[src:sheep/abraham] These people believed not in one God but in many gods, to whom they ascribed miracles, and hence they all rose up against Abraham.
[src:sheep/abraham] No one supported him except his nephew Lot and "one or two other individuals of no consequence".
[src:sheep/abraham] At last the intensity of his enemies' opposition obliged him, utterly wronged, to forsake his native land.
[src:sheep/abraham] Abraham then came to "these regions", that is, to the Holy Land.
[src:sheep/abraham] To Bahá'u'lláh, the "Voice of God" commanded Abraham to offer up Ishmael as a sacrifice, so that his steadfastness in the faith of God and his detachment from all else but him may be demonstrated unto men.
[src:sheep/abraham] The purpose of God, moreover, was to sacrifice him as a ransom for the sins and iniquities of all the peoples of the earth.
[src:sheep/abraham] In the Baháʼí texts, like the Islamic texts, Abraham is often referred to as "the Friend of God".
[src:sheep/abraham] 'Abdu'l-Bahá described Abraham as the founder of monotheism.
[src:sheep/abraham] ʻAbdu'l-Bahá also suggested the "holy manifestations who have been the sources or founders of the various religious systems" were united and agreed in purpose and teaching, and the Abraham, Moses, Zoroaster, the Buddha, Jesus, Muhammad, the Báb and Bahá'u'lláh are one in "spirit and reality".
[src:sheep/abraham] Paintings on the life of Abraham tend to focus on only a few incidents: the sacrifice of Isaac; meeting Melchizedek; entertaining the three angels; Hagar in the desert; and a few others.
[src:sheep/abraham] Additionally, Martin O'Kane, a professor of Biblical Studies, writes that the parable of Lazarus resting in the "Bosom of Abraham", as described in the Gospel of Luke, became an iconic image in Christian works.
[src:sheep/abraham] According to O'Kane, artists often chose to divert from the common literary portrayal of Lazarus sitting next to Abraham at a banquet in Heaven and instead focus on the "somewhat incongruous notion of Abraham, the most venerated of patriarchs, holding a naked and vulnerable child in his bosom".
[src:sheep/abraham] Several artists have been inspired by the life of Abraham, including Albrecht Dürer (1471–1528), Caravaggio (1573–1610), Donatello, Raphael, Philip van Dyck (Dutch painter, 1680–1753), and Claude Lorrain (French painter, 1600–1682).
[src:sheep/abraham] The Sarcophagus of Junius Bassus depicts a set of biblical stories, including Abraham about to sacrifice Isaac.
[src:sheep/abraham] These sculpted scenes are on the outside of a marble Early Christian sarcophagus used for the burial of Junius Bassus.
[src:sheep/abraham] This sarcophagus has been described as "probably the single most famous piece of early Christian relief sculpture." The sarcophagus was originally placed in or under Old St.
[src:sheep/abraham] Peter's Basilica, was rediscovered in 1597, and is now below the modern basilica in the Museo Storico del Tesoro della Basilica di San Pietro (Museum of St.
[src:sheep/abraham] The base is approximately 4 ft × 8 ft × 4 ft (1.2 m × 2.4 m × 1.2 m).
[src:sheep/abraham] George Segal created figural sculptures by molding plastered gauze strips over live models in his 1987 work *Abraham's Farewell to Ishmael*.
[src:sheep/abraham] The human condition was central to his concerns, and Segal used the Old Testament as a source for his imagery.
[src:sheep/abraham] This sculpture depicts the dilemma faced by Abraham when Sarah demanded that he expel Hagar and Ishmael.
[src:sheep/abraham] In the sculpture, the father's tenderness, Sarah's rage, and Hagar's resigned acceptance portray a range of human emotions.
[src:sheep/abraham] The sculpture was donated to the Miami Art Museum after the artist's death in 2000.
[src:sheep/abraham] Abraham can sometimes be identified by the context of the image – the meeting with Melchizedek, the three visitors, or the sacrifice of Isaac.
[src:sheep/abraham] In solo portraits a sword or knife may be used as his accessory, as in this statue by Giovanni Maria Morlaiter or this painting by Lorenzo Monaco.
[src:sheep/abraham] As early as the beginning of the 3rd century, Christian art followed Christian typology in making the sacrifice of Isaac a foreshadowing of Christ's sacrifice on the cross, and its memorial in the sacrifice of the Mass.
[src:sheep/abraham] See for example this 11th-century Christian altar engraved with Abraham's and other sacrifices taken to prefigure that of Christ in the Eucharist.
[src:sheep/abraham] Some early Christian writers interpreted the three visitors as the triune God.
[src:sheep/abraham] Thus in Santa Maria Maggiore, Rome, a 5th-century mosaic portrays only the visitors against a gold ground and puts semitransparent copies of them in the "heavenly" space above the scene.
[src:sheep/abraham] In Eastern Orthodox art, the visit is the chief means by which the Trinity is pictured (example).
[src:sheep/abraham] Some images do not include Abraham and Sarah, like Andrei Rublev's *Trinity*, which shows only the three visitors as beardless youths at a table.
[src:sheep/abraham] In 1681, Marc-Antoine Charpentier released a Dramatic motet (Oratorio), **Sacrificim Abrahae** H.402 – 402 a – 402 b, for soloists, chorus, doubling instruments and continuo.
[src:sheep/abraham] Sébastien de Brossard composed a cantata **Abraham ou le sacrifice d'Isaac** between 1703 and 1708.
[src:sheep/abraham] In 1994, Steve Reich released an opera named *The Cave*.
[src:sheep/abraham] The title refers to the Cave of the Patriarchs.
[src:sheep/abraham] The narrative of the opera is based on the story of Abraham, and his immediate family, as it is recounted in religious texts, and understood by individuals from different cultures and religious traditions.
[src:sheep/abraham] The eponymous track on Bob Dylan's 1965 album *Highway 61 Revisited* contains five stanzas, with someone in each describing an unusual problem that is ultimately resolved on Highway 61.
[src:sheep/abraham] In the first stanza, God tells Abraham to "kill me a son".
[src:sheep/abraham] God wants the killing done on Highway 61.
[src:sheep/abraham] *Abram*, the birth name of Abraham, is also the name of Dylan's father.
[src:sheep/abraham] In 2004, *Rolling Stone* magazine ranked "Highway 61 Revisited" at number 364 in their 500 Greatest Songs of All Time.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] The religions of this set share doctrinal, historical, and geographic overlap that contrast them with Indian religions, Iranian religions, and East Asian religions, although some smaller Abrahamic religions, such as the Baha'i Faith, are also Iranian religions.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] Judaism, Christianity, and Islam, are the three largest Abrahamic religions, with Christianity and Islam being followed and adhered to by around half of the world's population.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] However, the term has been criticized by some scholars for reportedly oversimplifying cultural and doctrinal nuances between the different religions.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] The term *Abrahamic religions* (and its variations) is a collective religious descriptor for similar and closely related elements shared by Judaism, Christianity, and Islam, as well as the smaller religions such as the Baháʼí Faith, the Druze faith, Rastafari, and Samaritanism.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] It features prominently in interfaith dialogue and civil discourse, as well as academic discourse.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] The term appears for the first time in the second half of the 20th century.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] Although historically the term *Abrahamic religions* was limited to just Judaism, Christianity, and Islam, restricting the category to these three religions has come under criticism.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] The late-19th-century Baháʼí Faith has been characterized as Abrahamic, as it is a monotheistic religion that recognizes its own descent from Abraham.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] The figure of Abraham is suggested as a common ground for Judaism, Christianity, Islam, as well as Samaritanism, the Druze Faith, the Baha'i Faith, and Rastafari and a hypothesized eschatological reconciliation of the seven religions.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] Commonalities may include creation, revelation, and redemption, but such shared concepts vary significantly between and within the Abrahamic religions themselves.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] Proponents of the term argue that all seven religions are united through the deity worshipped by Abraham.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] The Catholic scholar of Islam Louis Massignon argued that the phrase "Abrahamic religion" means that the religions come from one spiritual source.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] The modern term comes from the plural form of a Quranic reference to *dīn Ibrāhīm* ("religion of Abraham").
[src:sheep/abrahamic] In Christianity, Paul the Apostle, in Romans 4:11–12, refers to Abraham as "father of all", including those "who have faith, circumcised or uncircumcised." From its founding, Islam likewise conceived of itself as the "religion of Abraham".
[src:sheep/abrahamic] The Bahá’í scriptures state that the religion's founder, Baháʼu'lláh, descended from Abraham through his wife Keturah's sons.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] The appropriateness of grouping Judaism, Christianity, and Islam as "Abrahamic religions" and related terms has been challenged.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] Adam Dodds argues that the term "Abrahamic faiths", while helpful, can be misleading, as it conveys an unspecified historical and theological commonality that is problematic on closer examination.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] While there is commonality among the religions, their shared ancestry is mainly peripheral to their respective foundational theological claims, practices, and cultures, concealing irreconcilable differences.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] The common Christian doctrines of Jesus's Incarnation, the Trinity, and the resurrection of Jesus, for example, are accepted in neither Judaism nor Islam.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] Jewish tradition claims that the Twelve Tribes of Israel are descended from Abraham through his son Isaac and grandson Jacob, whose sons formed the nation of the Israelites in Canaan.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] In its early stages, the Israelite religion (Yahwism) shares traits with the Canaanite religions of the Bronze Age; by the Iron Age, it had become distinct from other Canaanite religions as it shed polytheism for monolatry.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] They understood their relationship with their god, Yahweh, as a covenant and that the deity promised Abraham a permanent homeland.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] The monolatrist nature of Yahwism was further developed in the period following the Babylonian captivity, eventually emerging as a firm religious movement of monotheism.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] With the Fall of Babylon, Judaism incorporated concepts such as messianism, belief in free will and judgement after death, conception of heaven and hell, angels and demons, among others, into their belief-system.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] Christianity traces back their origin to the 1st century and refers to themselves as a continuation of Judaism (commonly referred to as the old covenant) initially led by Jesus.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] His followers viewed him as the Messiah, as in the Confession of Peter; after his crucifixion and death they came to view him as God incarnate, who was resurrected and will return at the end of time to judge the living and the dead and create an eternal Kingdom of God.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] In the 1st century AD, under the Apostles of Jesus of Nazareth; Christianity spread widely.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] Paul the Apostle interpreted the role of Abraham differently from the Jews of his time.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] While for the Jews, Abraham was considered a loyal monotheist in a polytheistic environment, Paul celebrates Abraham as a man who found faith in God before adhering to religious law.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] In contrast to Judaism, adherence to religious law becomes associated with idolatry.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] While Christians fashioned their religion around Jesus of Nazareth, the siege of Jerusalem (70 CE), forced Jews to reconcile their belief-system with the destruction of the Second Temple and associated rituals.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] At this time, both Judaism and Christianity had to systematize their scriptures and beliefs, resulting in competing theologies both claiming Abrahamic heritage.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] Christians could hardly dismiss the Hebrew scriptures as Jesus himself refers to them according to Christian reports, and parallels between Jesus and the Biblical stories of *creation* and *redemption* starting with Abraham in the *Book of Genesis*.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] The distant God asserted by Jesus according to the Christians, created a form of dualism between Creator and creation and the doctrine of *Creatio ex nihilo*, which later heavily influenced Jewish and Islamic theology.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] By that, Christians established their own identity, distinct from both Greeks and Jews, as those who venerate and worship the deity of Jesus.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] After several periods of alternating persecution and relative peace *vis-à-vis* the Roman authorities under different administrations, Christianity became the state church of the Roman Empire in 380, but has been split into various churches from its beginning.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] An attempt was made by the Byzantine Empire to unify Christendom, but this formally failed with the East–West Schism of 1054.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] In the 16th century, the birth and growth of Protestantism during the Reformation further split Christianity into many denominations.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] Christianity remains culturally diverse in its Western and Eastern branches, Christianity played a prominent role in the development of Western civilization.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] Islam is based on the teachings of the Quran.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] Although it considers Muhammad to be the Seal of the prophets, Islam teaches that every prophet preached Islam, as the word *Islam* means submission, the main concept preached by all prophets.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] The Quran also mentions God having revealed the Scrolls of Abraham and the Scrolls of Moses.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] Islamic tradition claims that twelve Arab tribes known as the Ishmaelites are descended from Abraham through his son Ishmael in the Arabian Peninsula.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] The relationship between Islamic and Hebrew scriptures and New Testament differs significantly from the relationship between the New Testament and the Hebrew Bible.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] In the 7th century AD, Islam was founded by Muhammad in the Arabian Peninsula; it spread widely through the early Muslim conquests, shortly after his death.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] Islam understands its form of "Abrahamic monotheism" as preceding both Judaism and Christianity, and in contrast with Arabian Henotheism.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] The teachings of the Quran are believed by Muslims to be the direct and final revelation and words of God.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] Islam, like Christianity, is a universal religion (i.e. membership is open to anyone).
[src:sheep/abrahamic] Like Judaism, it has a strictly unitary conception of God, called *tawhid* or "strict monotheism".
[src:sheep/abrahamic] The story of the creation of the world in the Quran is elaborated less extensively than in the Hebrew scripture, emphasizing the transcendence and universality of God, instead.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] According to the Quran, God says *kun fa-yakūnu*.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] The Quran describes God as the creator of "heavens and earth", to emphasize that it is a universal God and not a local Arabian deity.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] Samaritanism is considered by some fringe Jewish and Christian apologetics to be a sect which diverged from Judaism in the 6th to 3rd centuries BCE.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] There is growing archaeological, DNA testing, and textual evidence in modern times which has proved the status of the Israelite Samaritans as an independent Abrahamic ethnoreligion and indigenous people of the Levant in their own right.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] The evidence has authenticated their claim to a legal religious status.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] Some sources consider Mandaeism to be an Abrahamic religion – however, that classification is controversial, given that Mandaeism does not accept Abraham as a prophet, despite revering as prophets several other figures from the Jewish scriptures.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] On the contrary, the Mandaeans believe that Abraham was originally a priest of their religion, but became an apostate from it.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] Druze is another religion which emerged from Islam in the 11th century, and hence is sometimes also considered an Abrahamic religion.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] Yazidism, another Kurdish religion, is considered a syncretic religion and shares elements with Shia Islam, Mandaeism, Christianity, and Judaism, including a belief in Adam and Abraham.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] It has also been influenced by Islamic mysticism and Gnostic Christianity.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] In Yazidism, the prophet Abraham is invoked during prayers before a meal, especially ritual meals.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] A number of sources include the Baháʼí Faith, established in the 19th century, since it historically emerged in an Islamic milieu, and shares several beliefs with the Abrahamic faiths, including monotheism and recognising Jewish, Christian and Islamic figures as prophets.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] Some scholars include Bábism, a 19th-century movement and precursor to the Baháʼí Faith.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] Rastafari, an Afrocentric religion which emerged from Christianity in 1930s Jamaica, is also sometimes classified as Abrahamic, in particular due to its monotheism and use of the Bible as scripture.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] Abrahamic religions agree upon the createdness of the universe by God, who is conceived of as eternal, omnipotent, and omniscient.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] All three identify the creator of the universe with the God revealed to Abraham.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] However, they differ on how to conceptualize God.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] Christianity proposes God's utter transcendence and that an intermediary — such as an incarnation of God — is required to bridge the gap between God and humans.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] According to Islam, God is knowable through his creation, metaphorical stories of the prophets stored in the Quran, and signs in nature.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] Christianity proposes God's personhood in the form of a Son of God as an aspect of the Divinity as formulated in the doctrine of the Trinity.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] In contrast, God in Islam is less personal than described in the Judeo-Christian tradition, and more of a mysterious power behind all aspects of the universe.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] Their religious texts feature many of the same figures, histories, and places, although they often present them with different roles, perspectives, and meanings.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] Believers who agree on these similarities and the common Abrahamic origin tend to also be more positive towards other Abrahamic groups.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] Religious law in Judaism and Samaritanism commands that males be circumcised when they are eight days old, as does the *sunnah* ('tradition') in Islam.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] Despite its common practice in Muslim-majority nations, circumcision is considered to be *sunnah* and not required for a life directed by Allah.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] Although there is some debate within Islam over whether it is a religious requirement or mere recommendation, circumcision (called *khitan*) is practiced nearly universally by Muslim males.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] Today, many Christian denominations are neutral about ritual male circumcision, neither requiring it for religious observance nor forbidding it for cultural or other reasons.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] Western Christianity replaced the custom of male circumcision with the ritual of baptism, a ceremony which varies according to the doctrine of the denomination, but it generally includes immersion, aspersion, or anointment with water.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] The Early Church, as recorded in Acts 15 at the Council of Jerusalem, decided that Gentile Christians are not required to undergo circumcision.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] The Council of Florence in the 15th century prohibited it.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] Paragraph #2297 of the Catechism of the Catholic Church calls non-medical amputation or mutilation immoral.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] By the 21st century, the Catholic Church had adopted a neutral position on the practice, as long as it was not practised as an initiation ritual.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] Catholic scholars make various arguments in support of the idea that this policy is not in contradiction with the previous edicts.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] The New Testament, in Acts 15, records that Christianity did not require circumcision.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] Coptic Christians practice circumcision as a rite of passage.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] The Eritrean Orthodox Church and the Ethiopian Orthodox Tewahedo Church calls for circumcision, with near-universal prevalence among Orthodox men in Ethiopia.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] Many countries with majorities of Christian adherents in Europe and Latin America have low circumcision rates.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] In contrast, both religious and non-religious circumcision is widely practiced in many predominantly Christian countries and among Christian communities in the Anglosphere countries, Oceania, South Korea, the Philippines, the Middle East and Africa.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] Countries such as the United States, the Philippines, Australia (albeit primarily in the older generations), Canada, Cameroon, Democratic Republic of the Congo, Ethiopia, Equatorial Guinea, Ghana, Nigeria, Kenya, and many other African Christian countries have high circumcision rates.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] Circumcision is near universal in the Christian countries of Oceania.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] In some African and Eastern Christian denominations male circumcision is an integral or established practice, and require that their male members undergo circumcision.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] Coptic Christianity and Ethiopian Orthodoxy and Eritrean Orthodoxy still observe male circumcision and practice circumcision as a rite of passage.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] Male circumcision is also widely practiced among Christians from Egypt, Syria, Lebanon, Jordan, Palestine, Israel, and North Africa.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] Male circumcision is among the rites of Islam and is part of the *fitrah*, or the innate disposition and natural character and instinct of the human creation.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] Although circumcision is widely practiced among the Druze, it is performed as a cultural tradition and has no religious significance in the Druze faith.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] Some Druze do not circumcise their male children, and refuse to observe this "common Muslim practice".
[src:sheep/abrahamic] Circumcision is not a religious practice of the Bahá'í Faith, and the decision is left to the parents.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] Judaism accepts converts, but has had no explicit missionaries since the end of the Second Temple period.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] Judaism states that non-Jews can achieve righteousness by following Noahide Laws, a set of moral imperatives that, according to the Talmud, were given by God as a binding set of laws for the "children of Noah"—that is, all of humanity.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] It is believed that as much as 10% of the Roman Empire followed Judaism either as fully ritually obligated Jews or the simpler rituals required of non-Jewish members of that faith.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] In the U.S., as of 2003, 28% of married Jews were married to non-Jews.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] Many Christian organizations, especially Protestant churches, send missionaries to non-Christian communities throughout the world.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] Forced conversions to Catholicism have happened at various points throughout history.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] Forced conversions to Protestantism has occurred as well, notably during the Reformation, especially in England and Ireland (see recusancy and Popish plot).
[src:sheep/abrahamic] Forced conversions are now condemned as sinful by major denominations such as the Roman Catholic Church, which officially states that forced conversions pollute the Christian religion and offend human dignity, so that past or present offences are regarded as a scandal (a cause of unbelief).
[src:sheep/abrahamic] According to Pope Paul VI, "It is one of the major tenets of Catholic doctrine that man's response to God in faith must be free: no one, therefore, is to be forced to embrace the Christian faith against his own will." The Roman Catholic Church has declared that Catholics should fight anti-Semitism.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] Islam encourages proselytism in various forms.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] Dawah is an important Islamic concept that denotes the preaching of Islam.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] Da‘wah literally means "issuing a summons" or "making an invitation".
[src:sheep/abrahamic] A Muslim who practices da‘wah, either as a religious worker or in a volunteer community effort, is called a dā‘ī, plural du‘āt.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] A dā‘ī is thus a person who invites people to understand Islam through a dialogical process and may be categorized in some cases as the Islamic equivalent of a missionary, as one who invites people to the faith, to the prayer, or to Islamic life.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] Some pursue Islamic studies specifically to perform Da'wah.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] Mosques and other Islamic centers sometimes actively spread Da'wah, similar to evangelical churches.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] Others consider being open to the public and answering questions to be Da'wah.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] Recalling Muslims to the faith and expanding their knowledge can also be considered Da'wah.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] In Islamic theology, the purpose of Da'wah is to invite people, both Muslims and non-Muslims, to understand the commandments of God as expressed in the Quran and the Sunnah of the Prophet, as well as to inform them about Muhammad.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] Da'wah produces converts to Islam, which in turn grows the size of the Muslim Ummah, or community of Muslims.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] While there were instances of forced conversions to Islam, these were neither the norm nor part of a systematic strategy of expansion.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] Many Muslim rulers practiced religious pluralism, and the Quran explicitly prohibits compulsion in matters of faith.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] Most conversions to Islam occurred gradually, driven by social, cultural, and economic influences rather than coercion.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] However, forcible conversion continues to be practiced in parts of the Islamic world.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] Christianity is the largest Abrahamic religion with about 2.5 billion adherents, called Christians, constituting about 31.1% of the world's population.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] Islam is the second largest Abrahamic religion, as well as the fastest-growing Abrahamic religion in recent decades.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] It has about 2.0 billion adherents, called Muslims, constituting about 24.1% of the world's population.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] The third largest Abrahamic religion is Judaism with about 14.1 million adherents, called Jews.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] The Baháʼí Faith has over 8 million adherents, making it the fourth largest Abrahamic religion, and the fastest growing religion across the 20th century, usually at least twice the rate of population growth.
[src:sheep/abrahamic] The Druze faith has between one million and nearly two million adherents.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Sheep are most likely descended from the wild mouflon of Europe and Asia, with Iran being a geographic envelope of the domestication center.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] One of the earliest animals to be domesticated for agricultural purposes, sheep are raised for fleeces, meat (lamb, hogget, or mutton), and sheep milk.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] A sheep's wool is the most widely used animal fiber, and is usually harvested by shearing.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Ovine meat is called lamb and mutton, with lamb describing meat from younger animals and mutton meat from older ones.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Sheep continue to be important for wool and meat today, and are also occasionally raised for pelts, as dairy animals, or as model organisms for science.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Sheep husbandry is done throughout the majority of the inhabited world.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] It was central to agriculture and textiles throughout Eurasia for millennia.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] In the 21st century, Australia, New Zealand, nations of southern and western South America, South Africa, and the British Isles are most closely associated with sheep production.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] More recently, China and India host among the largest flocks by absolute count, if as a smaller proportion of their economy.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] There is a large lexicon of unique terms for sheep husbandry which vary considerably by region and dialect.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Use of the word *sheep* began in Middle English as a derivation of the Old English word **scēap**.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Many other specific terms for the various life stages of sheep exist, generally related to lambing, shearing, and age.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] As a key animal in the history of farming, sheep have an entrenched place in human culture.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Sheep terminology and idiom are common in language and symbolism.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] As livestock, sheep are most often associated with pastoral, Arcadian imagery.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Sheep figure in many mythologies—such as the Golden Fleece—and major religions, especially the Abrahamic traditions.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] In both ancient and modern religious ritual, sheep are used as sacrificial animals.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] The exact line of descent from wild ancestors to domestic sheep is unclear.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] The most common hypothesis states that *Ovis aries* is descended from the Asiatic (*O. gmelini*) species of mouflon; the European mouflon (*Ovis aries musimon*) is a direct descendant of this population.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] The rearing of sheep for secondary products, and the resulting breed development, began in either southwest Asia or western Europe.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Initially, sheep were kept for meat, milk, and skins, not their fleece.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Archaeological evidence from statuary found at sites in Iran suggests that selection for woolly sheep may have begun around 6000 BC, and the earliest woven wool garments have been dated to around 4000 BC, two thousand years later.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Sheep husbandry spread quickly in Europe.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Excavations show that in about 6000 BC, during the Neolithic period of prehistory, the Castelnovien people, living around Châteauneuf-les-Martigues near present-day Marseille in the south of France, were among the first in Europe to keep domestic sheep.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Practically from its inception, ancient Greek civilization relied on sheep as primary livestock, and were even said to name individual animals.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Ancient Romans kept sheep on a wide scale, and were an important agent in the spread of sheep raising.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Pliny the Elder, in his Natural History (*Naturalis Historia*), speaks at length about sheep and wool.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] European colonists spread the practice to the New World from 1493 onwards.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Domestic sheep are relatively small ruminants, usually with a crimped hair called wool and often with horns forming a lateral spiral.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] They differ from their wild relatives and ancestors in several respects, having become uniquely neotenic as a result of selective breeding by humans.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] A few primitive breeds of sheep retain some of the characteristics of their wild cousins, such as short tails.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Depending on breed, domestic sheep may have no horns at all (i.e. polled), or horns in both sexes, or in males only.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Most horned breeds have a single pair, but a few breeds may have several horns, such as Jacob sheep.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Another trait unique to domestic sheep as compared to wild ovines is their wide variation in color.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Wild sheep are largely variations of brown hues, and variation within species is extremely limited.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Colors of domestic sheep range from pure white to dark chocolate brown, and even spotted or piebald.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Sheep keepers also sometimes artificially paint "smit marks" onto their sheep in any pattern or color for identification.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Selection for easily dyeable white fleeces began early in sheep domestication, and as white wool is a dominant trait it spread quickly.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] However, colored sheep do appear in many modern breeds, and may even appear as a recessive trait in white flocks.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] While white wool is desirable for large commercial markets, there is a niche market for colored fleeces, mostly for handspinning.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] The nature of the fleece varies widely among the breeds, from dense and highly crimped, to long and hairlike.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] There is variation of wool type and quality even among members of the same flock, so wool classing is a step in the commercial processing of the fibre.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Depending on breed, sheep show a range of heights and weights.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Their rate of growth and mature weight is a heritable trait that is often selected for in breeding.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Ewes typically weigh between 45 and 100 kilograms (100 and 220 lb), and rams between 45 and 160 kilograms (100 and 350 lb).
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] When all deciduous teeth have erupted, the sheep has 20 teeth.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] As with other ruminants, the front teeth in the lower jaw bite against a hard, toothless dental pad in the upper jaw.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] These are used to pick off vegetation, then the rear teeth grind it before it is swallowed.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] There are eight lower front teeth in ruminants, but there is some disagreement as to whether these are eight incisors, or six incisors and two incisor-shaped canines.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] This means that the dental formula for sheep is either 0.0.3.34.0.3.3 or 0.0.3.33.1.3.3 There is a large diastema between the incisors and the molars.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] In the first few years of life one can calculate the age of sheep from their front teeth, as a first and second set of milk teeth are replaced by larger adult teeth.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] The full set of eight adult front teeth is complete at about four years of age.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] These teeth are then gradually ground down as sheep age and feed on pasture, making it harder for them to feed and hindering their health over time.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] For this reason, domestic sheep on normal pasture begin to slowly decline from four years on.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] The life expectancy of a sheep is 10 to 12 years, though some sheep may live as long as 20 years.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Ranchers often consider culling sheep not raised for meat around 6 years of age, although extra pasture or the sheep being an exceptional producer can encourage their handlers to continue keeping them.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Sheep have good hearing, and are sensitive to noise.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Sheep have horizontal slit-shaped pupils, with excellent peripheral vision; with visual fields of about 270° to 320°, sheep can see behind themselves without turning their heads.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Many breeds have only short hair on the face, and some have facial wool (if any) confined to the poll and or the area of the mandibular angle; the wide angles of peripheral vision apply to these breeds.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] A few breeds tend to have considerable wool on the face; for some individuals of these breeds, peripheral vision may be greatly reduced by "wool blindness", unless recently shorn about the face.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Sheep have poor depth perception; shadows and dips in the ground may cause sheep to baulk.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] In general, sheep have a tendency to move out of the dark and into well-lit areas, and prefer to move uphill when disturbed.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Sheep also have an excellent sense of smell, and, like all species of their genus, have scent glands just in front of the eyes, and interdigitally on the feet.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] The purpose of these glands is uncertain, but those on the face may be used in breeding behaviors.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] The foot glands might also be related to reproduction, but alternative functions, such as secretion of a waste product or a scent marker to help lost sheep find their flock, have also been proposed.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Sheep and goats are closely related: both are in the subfamily Caprinae.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] However, they are separate species, so hybrids rarely occur and are always infertile.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] A hybrid of a ewe and a buck (a male goat) is called a sheep-goat hybrid, known as *geep*.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Visual differences between sheep and goats include the beard of goats and divided upper lip (philtrum) of sheep.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Sheep tails also hang down, even when short or docked, while the short tails of goats are held upwards.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Also, sheep breeds are often naturally polled (either in both sexes or just in the female), while naturally polled goats are rare (though many are polled artificially).
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Males of the two species differ in that buck goats acquire a unique and strong odor during the rut, whereas rams do not.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] The domestic sheep is a multi-purpose animal.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] More than 200 breeds are recognized, created and bred to serve diverse purposes.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Some sources who use the term more freely give counts exceeding a thousand different breeds. although most sources do not recognize the marginal and sub-breeds included in larger counts.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] The Food and Agriculture Organization of the UN (FAO) listed 1229 breeds as of 2006.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Sheep are usually classified as being best suited to furnishing a certain product: wool, meat, milk, hides, or a combination.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Other features used when classifying sheep include face color (generally white or black), tail length, presence or lack of horns, and the topography for which the breed has been developed.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] This last point is stressed in the UK, where breeds are described as either upland (hill or mountain) or lowland breeds.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] A sheep may also be of a fat-tailed type, with larger deposits of fat within and around its tail.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] In the wild, this fat tail could store nutrients, a useful trait in arid environments.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] In cultivation, they are generally dual-purpose sheep common in Africa and Asia.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Breeds are often categorized by the type of their wool.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Fine wool breeds are those that have wool of great crimp and density, which are preferred for textiles.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Most of these were derived from Merino sheep, and the breed continues to dominate the world sheep industry.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Downs breeds have wool between the extremes, and are typically fast-growing meat and ram breeds with dark faces.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Some major medium wool breeds, such as the Corriedale, are dual-purpose crosses of long and fine-wooled breeds and were created for high-production commercial flocks.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Long wool breeds are the largest of sheep, with long wool and a slow rate of growth.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Long wool sheep are valued for crossbreeding and have been used to create new, merged sheep types.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] For example, the American Columbia breed was developed by crossing Lincoln rams (a long wool breed) with fine-wooled Rambouillet ewes.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Coarse or carpet wool sheep are those with a medium to long length wool of characteristic coarseness.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Breeds traditionally used for carpet wool show great variability, but the chief requirement is a wool that will not break down under heavy use (as would that of the finer breeds).
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] As the demand for carpet-quality wool declines, some breeders of this type of sheep are attempting to use a few of these traditional breeds for alternative purposes.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Others have always been primarily meat-class sheep.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] A minor class of sheep are the dairy breeds.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Dual-purpose breeds that may primarily be meat or wool sheep are often used secondarily as milking animals, but there are a few breeds that are predominantly used for milking.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] These sheep produce a higher quantity of milk and have slightly longer lactation curves.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] In the quality of their milk, the fat and protein content percentages of dairy sheep vary from non-dairy breeds, but lactose content does not.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] A last group of sheep breeds is that of fur or hair sheep, which do not grow wool at all.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Hair sheep are similar to the early domesticated sheep kept before woolly breeds were developed, and are raised for meat and pelts.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Some modern breeds of hair sheep, such as the Dorper, result from crosses between wool and hair breeds.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] For meat producers, hair sheep are cheaper to keep, as they do not need shearing.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Hair sheep are also more resistant to parasites and hot weather.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] The 20th and 21st century have seen the rise of corporate agribusiness and the decline of localized family farms.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Large sheep holders generally favor keeping just the "best" breeds for the land and pasture they have available, in particular favoring fast-growing and fertile breeds.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] This has had the result that many breeds of sheep are in danger of extinction.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] The Rare Breeds Survival Trust estimated in 2008 that 22 breeds native to the United Kingdom as having 3,000 registered animals (each) or fewer, and The Livestock Conservancy listed 8 North American breeds as either "critical" or "threatened" in 2008.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Heritage or heirloom breeds have been pushed to the margins of the sheep industry.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Most breeds prefer to graze on grass and other short roughage, avoiding the taller woody parts of plants that goats readily consume.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Both sheep and goats use their lips and tongues to select parts of the plant that are easier to digest or higher in nutrition.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Sheep, however, graze well in monoculture pastures where most goats fare poorly.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Like all ruminants, sheep have a complex digestive system composed of four chambers, allowing them to break down cellulose from stems, leaves, and seed hulls into simpler carbohydrates.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] When sheep graze, vegetation is chewed into a mass called a bolus, which is then passed into the rumen, via the reticulum.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] The rumen is a 19- to 38-liter (5 to 10 gallon) organ in which feed is fermented.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] The fermenting organisms include bacteria, fungi, and protozoa.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] (Other important rumen organisms include some archaea, which produce methane from carbon dioxide.) The bolus is periodically regurgitated back to the mouth as cud for additional chewing and salivation.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] After fermentation in the rumen, feed passes into the reticulum and the omasum.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Some feeds such as grains spend little time in the rumen and ferment rapidly.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] After the first three chambers, food moves into the abomasum for final digestion before processing by the intestines.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] The abomasum is the chamber most analogous to a human stomach in operation, and is sometimes called the "true stomach".
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Other than forage, the other staple feed for sheep is hay, often during the winter months.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] The ability to thrive solely on pasture (even without hay) varies with breed, but all sheep can survive on this diet.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Sheep also require minerals in their diet, either in a trace mix or from salt licks.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] One complication with sheep husbandry is that sheep are substantially more vulnerable to copper toxicity than other livestock.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Copper, while needed in small quantities, becomes in large quantities a cumulative poison to sheep that is excreted very slowly.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Sheep feeding on certain plants such as heliotropes can cause stored copper in the liver to be discharged en masse, resulting in sudden death.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Careless farmers supplying to their flock mineral supplements designed for cattle, pigs, or horses that contain too much copper can cause sickness and death.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Sheep follow a diurnal pattern of activity, feeding from dawn to dusk, stopping sporadically to rest and chew their cud.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Ideal pasture for sheep is not lawnlike grass, but an array of grasses, legumes and forbs.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Types of land where sheep are raised vary widely, from pastures that are seeded and improved intentionally to rough, native lands.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Common plants toxic to sheep are present in most of the world, and include (but are not limited to) cherry, some oaks and acorns, tomato, yew, rhubarb, potato, and rhododendron.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Just a few leaves of rhododendrons such as Azaleas can be lethal.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Sheep are largely grazing herbivores, unlike browsing animals such as goats and deer that prefer taller foliage.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] With a much narrower face and a split upper lip, sheep crop plants very close to the ground and can overgraze a pasture much faster than cattle.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] For this reason, many shepherds use managed intensive rotational grazing, where a flock is rotated through multiple pastures, giving plants time to recover.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Sheep can both cause and solve the spread of invasive plant species.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] By disturbing the natural state of pasture, sheep and other livestock can pave the way for invasive plants.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] However, sheep also prefer to eat invasives such as cheatgrass, leafy spurge, kudzu and spotted knapweed over native species such as sagebrush, making grazing sheep effective for conservation grazing.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Research conducted in Imperial County, California compared lamb grazing with herbicides for weed control in seedling alfalfa fields.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Three trials demonstrated that grazing lambs were just as effective as herbicides in controlling winter weeds.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Entomologists also compared grazing lambs to insecticides for insect control in winter alfalfa.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] In this trial, lambs provided insect control as effectively as insecticides.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Sheep grazing labor has also been used to a limited extent for controlling hazardous species such as giant hogweed.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] In the 21st century, sheep have been used in agrivoltaics, grazing plants near solar power arrays.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Sheep are flock animals and strongly gregarious; much sheep behavior can be understood on the basis of these tendencies.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] The dominance hierarchy of sheep and their natural inclination to follow a leader to new pastures were the pivotal factors in sheep being one of the first domesticated livestock species.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Furthermore, in contrast to the red deer and gazelle (two other ungulates of primary importance to meat production in prehistoric times), sheep do not defend territories although they do form home ranges.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] All sheep have a tendency to congregate close to other members of a flock, although this behavior varies with breed; sheep can become stressed when separated from their flock members.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] During flocking, sheep have a strong tendency to follow, and a leader may simply be the first individual to move.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Relationships in flocks tend to be closest among related sheep: in mixed-breed flocks, subgroups of the same breed tend to form, and a ewe and her direct descendants often move as a unit within large flocks.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Sheep can become hefted to one particular local pasture (heft) so they do not roam freely in unfenced landscapes.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Lambs learn the heft from ewes and if whole flocks are culled it must be retaught to the replacement animals.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Flock behavior in sheep is generally only exhibited in groups of four or more sheep; fewer sheep may not react as expected when alone or with few other sheep.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Being a prey species, the primary defense mechanism of sheep is to flee from danger when their flight zone is entered.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Cornered sheep may warn via any of hoof stamping, jumping, or adopting an aggressive posture.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] They will charge and butt if they decide to fight, most notably for ewes protecting newborn lambs, and rams.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] The English verb "ram" directly comes from male sheep charging at targets of their ire, "ramming" them.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] In regions where sheep have no natural predators, none of the native breeds of sheep exhibit a strong flocking behavior.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Farmers exploit flocking behavior to keep sheep together on unfenced pastures such as in hill farming, and to move them more easily.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] For this purpose shepherds often use herding dogs.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Humans can also herd sheep directly, most effectively with a promise of food, such as presenting a bucket of feed to them and carrying it in the desired direction.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Association of humans with regular feeding results in sheep soliciting humans, essentially taking the behavior lambs have with their mothers and applying it to humans as well (e.g. bleating or pressing their noses for attention and food).
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Sheep establish a dominance hierarchy through fighting, threats and competitiveness.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Dominant animals are inclined to be more aggressive with other sheep, and usually feed first at troughs.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Primarily among rams, horn size is a factor in the flock hierarchy.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Rams with different size horns may be less inclined to fight to establish the dominance order, while rams with similarly sized horns are more so.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Merinos have an almost linear hierarchy whereas there is a less rigid structure in Border Leicesters when a competitive feeding situation arises.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] In sheep, position in a moving flock is highly correlated with social dominance, but there is no definitive study to show consistent voluntary leadership by an individual sheep.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Sheep are frequently thought of as unintelligent animals.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Despite these perceptions, a University of Illinois monograph on sheep reported their intelligence to be just below that of pigs and on par with that of cattle.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] In a study published in *Nature* in 2001, Kenneth M.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Kendrick and others reported; "Sheep recognize and are attracted to individual sheep and humans by their faces, as they possess similar specialized neural systems in the temporal and frontal lobes ... individual sheep can remember 50 other different sheep faces for over 2 years".
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] In addition to long-term facial recognition of individuals, sheep can also differentiate emotional states through facial characteristics.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] If worked with patiently, sheep may learn their names, and many sheep are trained to be led by halter for showing and other purposes.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Sheep have also responded well to clicker training.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Rarely, sufficiently large sheep have been used as pack animals, largely in Central Asia, such as by the Xiongnu.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] A few places in Tibet and Nepal continue this tradition.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] It has been reported that some sheep have apparently shown problem-solving abilities; a flock in West Yorkshire, England, allegedly found a way to get over cattle grids by rolling on their backs, although documentation of this has relied on anecdotal accounts.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Sounds made by domestic sheep include bleats, grunts, rumbles and snorts.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Bleating ("baaing") is used mostly for contact communication, especially between dam and lambs, but also at times between other flock members.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] The bleats of individual sheep are distinctive, enabling the ewe and her lambs to recognize each other's vocalizations.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Vocal communication between lambs and their dam declines to a very low level within several weeks after parturition.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] A variety of bleats may be heard, depending on sheep age and circumstances.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Apart from contact communication, bleating may signal distress, frustration or impatience; however, sheep are usually silent when in pain.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Isolation commonly prompts bleating by sheep.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Rumbling sounds are made by the ram during courting; somewhat similar rumbling sounds may be made by the ewe, especially when with her neonate lambs.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] A snort (explosive exhalation through the nostrils) may signal aggression or a warning, and is often elicited from startled sheep.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] In sheep breeds lacking facial wool, the visual field is wide.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] In 10 sheep (Cambridge, Lleyn and Welsh Mountain breeds, which lack facial wool), the visual field ranged from 298° to 325°, averaging 313.1°, with binocular overlap ranging from 44.5° to 74°, averaging 61.7°.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] In some breeds, unshorn facial wool can limit the visual field; in some individuals, this may be enough to cause "wool blindness".
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] In addition to facial wool (in some breeds), visual field limitations can include ears and (in some breeds) horns, so the visual field can be extended by tilting the head.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Sheep eyes exhibit very low hyperopia and little astigmatism.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Such visual characteristics are likely to produce a well-focused retinal image of objects in both the middle and long distance.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Because sheep eyes have no accommodation, one might expect the image of very near objects to be blurred, but a rather clear near image could be provided by the tapetum and large retinal image of the sheep's eye, and adequate close vision may occur at muzzle length.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Good depth perception, inferred from the sheep's sure-footedness, was confirmed in "visual cliff" experiments; behavioral responses indicating depth perception are seen in lambs at one day old.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Sheep are thought to have colour vision, and can distinguish between a variety of colours: black, red, brown, green, yellow, and white.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Sight is a vital part of sheep communication, and when grazing, they maintain visual contact with each other.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Each sheep lifts its head upwards to check the position of other sheep in the flock.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] This constant monitoring is probably what keeps the sheep in a flock as they move along grazing.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Sheep become stressed when isolated; this stress is reduced if they are provided with a mirror, indicating that the sight of other sheep reduces stress.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Taste is the most important sense in sheep, establishing forage preferences, with sweet and sour plants being preferred and bitter plants being more commonly rejected.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Touch and sight are also important in relation to specific plant characteristics, such as succulence and growth form.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] The ram uses his vomeronasal organ (sometimes called the Jacobson's organ) to sense the pheromones of ewes and detect when they are in estrus.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] The ewe uses her vomeronasal organ for early recognition of her neonate lamb.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Sheep follow a similar reproductive strategy to other herd animals.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] A group of ewes is generally mated by a single ram, who has either been chosen by a breeder or, in feral populations, has established dominance through physical contest with other rams.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Most sheep are seasonal breeders, although some are able to breed year-round.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Ewes generally reach sexual maturity at six to eight months old, and rams generally at four to six months.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] For example, Finnsheep ewe lambs may reach puberty as early as 3 to 4 months, and Merino ewes sometimes reach puberty at 18 to 20 months.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Ewes have estrus cycles wherein they are in heat for around 30 hours on average every 17 days, although individual ewes can vary anywhere in a range of 12–48 hours.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Ewes exhibit few external signs of being in heat; the best signal is that they will follow rams around, then stand still to be mounted.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] This has led to the use of "teaser rams" (vasectomized or castrated rams) by shepherds to detect which ewes are still unmated and need more time with the mating ram, or to be culled.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] In feral sheep, rams may fight during the rut to determine which individuals may mate with ewes.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Rams, especially unfamiliar ones, will also fight outside the breeding period to establish dominance; rams can kill one another if allowed to mix freely.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] During the rut, even usually friendly rams may become aggressive towards humans due to increases in their hormone levels.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] After mating, sheep have a gestation period of about five months, and normal labor takes one to three hours.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Although some breeds regularly throw larger litters of lambs, most produce single or twin lambs.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] During or soon after labor, ewes and lambs may be confined to small lambing jugs, small pens designed to aid both careful observation of ewes and to cement the bond between them and their lambs.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] By selectively breeding ewes that produce multiple offspring with higher birth weights for generations, sheep producers have inadvertently caused some domestic sheep to have difficulty lambing compared to their wild brethren.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] It is in a sheep raiser's financial interest to intervene and assist such difficult lambing to save the ewe and her lamb, but this has reduced the influence of natural selection on encouraging easier and safer lambing, favoring instead higher peak productivity.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] In the case of problems, humans present at lambing can assist the ewe by extracting or repositioning lambs.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] After the birth, ewes ideally break the amniotic sac (if it is not broken during labor), and begin licking clean the lamb.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Most lambs will begin standing within an hour of birth.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] In normal situations, lambs nurse after standing, receiving vital colostrum milk.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Lambs that either fail to nurse or are rejected by the ewe require help to survive, such as bottle-feeding or fostering by another ewe.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Most lambs begin life being born outdoors.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] After lambs are several weeks old, lamb marking, ear tagging, docking, and castrating are carried out.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Vaccinations are usually applied in this period as well.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Ear tags with numbers are attached, or ear marks are applied, for ease of later identification of sheep.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Tail docking is commonly done 24–48 hours after birth (to avoid interference with maternal bonding and consumption of colostrum) and not later than one week after birth, to minimize pain, stress, recovery time and complications.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Castration of male lambs was once done promptly during the first week of life in 20th century practice, but now usually happens around three or four weeks of age.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] The first course of vaccinations (commonly anti-clostridial) is commonly given at an age of about 10 to 12 weeks; i.e. when the concentration of maternal antibodies passively acquired via colostrum is expected to have fallen low enough to permit development of active immunity.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Ewes are often revaccinated annually about 3 weeks before lambing, to provide high antibody concentrations in colostrum during the first several hours after lambing.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Ram lambs that will either be slaughtered or separated from ewes before sexual maturity are not usually castrated.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Mulesing is a controversial practice now on the decline that scars a sheep's hindquarters in order to reduce the risk of flystrike and require less frequent crutching; where still permitted, it is done from 2 to 8 weeks of age.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Objections to all these procedures have been raised by animal rights groups, but farmers defend them by saying they save money, and inflict only temporary pain.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Sheep are the only species of mammal except for humans which exhibit exclusive homosexual behavior.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] About 10% of rams refuse to mate with ewes but readily mate with other rams, and thirty percent of all rams demonstrate at least some homosexual behavior.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Additionally, a small number of females that were accompanied by a male fetus *in utero* (i.e. as fraternal twins) are freemartins (female animals that are behaviorally masculine and lack functioning ovaries).
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Sheep may fall victim to poisons, infectious diseases, and physical injuries.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] As a prey species, sheep try to hide signs of illness, to prevent being targeted by predators.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] This can cause unobservant shepherds to miss signs of a sheep in need.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] However, some signs of ill health are obvious, with sick sheep eating little, lying down excessively, and being generally listless.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Throughout history, much of the money and labor of sheep husbandry has aimed to prevent sheep ailments.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Historically, shepherds often created remedies by experimentation on the farm.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] In some developed countries, including the United States, sheep lack the economic importance for drug companies to perform expensive clinical trials required to approve more than a relatively limited number of drugs for ovine use.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Extra-label drug use in sheep production is permitted in many jurisdictions, subject to certain restrictions.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] In the 20th and 21st centuries, a minority of sheep owners have turned to alternative treatments such as homeopathy and herbalism to treat sheep veterinary problems.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] The effectiveness of alternative veterinary medicine has been met with skepticism by agricultural scientists.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Many breeders take a variety of preventive measures to ward off problems.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Regulating sheep intermixing can check the spread of disease from flock to flock.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] This can mean verifying sheep health before they are transferred or purchased, and quarantining new sheep for two or three weeks.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Good nutrition and good sanitation also greatly improve sheep health.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Avoiding poisons is important; common poisons sheep can encounter are pesticide sprays, inorganic fertilizer, motor oil, and radiator coolant containing ethylene glycol.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Reducing stress in sheep is also important for their health.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Restraint, isolation, loud noises, novel situations, pain, heat, extreme cold, fatigue and other stressors can lead to secretion of cortisol, a stress hormone, in amounts that may indicate welfare problems.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Excessive stress can compromise the immune system.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] "Shipping fever" (pneumonic mannheimiosis, formerly called pasteurellosis) is a disease of particular concern, that can occur as a result of stress, notably during transport and (or) handling.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Pain, fear and several other stressors can cause secretion of epinephrine (adrenaline).
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Considerable epinephrine secretion in the final days before slaughter can adversely affect meat quality (by causing glycogenolysis, removing the substrate for normal post-slaughter acidification of meat) and result in meat becoming more susceptible to colonization by spoilage bacteria.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Both external and internal parasites are the most prevalent malady in sheep, and can reduce their productivity or outright kill them.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] To deal with this, common forms of preventive medication for sheep are vaccinations and a variety of medicinal treatments.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Worms are the most common internal parasites, including roundworms, tapeworms, liver flukes, and others.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] They are ingested during grazing, incubate within the sheep, and are expelled through the digestive system, beginning the cycle again.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Worms can cause diarrhea (scouring) in mild cases, and death in severe cases.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Oral anti-parasitic medicines, known as drenches, are given to a flock to treat worms, sometimes after worm eggs in the feces has been counted to assess infestation levels.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Afterwards, sheep may be moved to a new pasture to avoid ingesting the same parasites.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] External sheep parasites include lice, sheep keds, nose bot flies, sheep itch mites, and maggots.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Keds are blood-sucking parasites that cause general malnutrition and decreased productivity, but are not fatal.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Maggots are those of the bot fly and the blow-fly, commonly *Lucilia sericata* or its relative *L. cuprina*.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Fly maggots cause the extremely destructive condition of flystrike.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Flies lay their eggs in wounds or wet, manure-soiled wool; when the maggots hatch they burrow into a sheep's flesh, eventually causing death if untreated.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] In addition to other treatments, crutching (shearing wool from a sheep's rump) is a common preventive method.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Some countries allow mulesing, a practice that involves stripping away the skin on the rump to prevent fly-strike, normally performed when the sheep is a lamb.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Nose bots are fly larvae that inhabit a sheep's sinuses, causing breathing difficulties and discomfort.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Common signs are a discharge from the nasal passage, sneezing, and frantic movement such as head shaking.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] External parasites may be controlled through the use of backliners, sprays, or immersive sheep dips.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] A wide array of bacterial and viral diseases affect sheep.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Diseases of the hoof, such as foot rot and foot scald may occur, and are treated with footbaths and other remedies.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Foot rot is present in over 97% of flocks in the UK.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] These painful conditions cause lameness and hinder feeding.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Ovine Johne's disease is a wasting disease that affects young sheep.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Bluetongue disease is an insect-borne illness causing fever and inflammation of the mucous membranes.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Ovine rinderpest (or *peste des petits ruminants*) is a highly contagious and often fatal viral disease affecting sheep and goats.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Sheep may also be affected by primary or secondary photosensitization.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Tetanus can also afflict sheep through wounds from shearing, docking, castration, or vaccination.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] The organism also can be introduced into the reproductive tract by unsanitary humans who assist ewes during lambing.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] A few sheep conditions are transmissible to humans.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Orf (also known as scabby mouth, contagious ecthyma or soremouth) is a skin disease leaving lesions that is transmitted through skin-to-skin contact.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Cutaneous anthrax is also called woolsorter's disease, as the spores can be transmitted in unwashed wool.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] More seriously, the organisms that can cause spontaneous enzootic abortion in sheep are easily transmitted to pregnant women.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Also of concern are the prion disease scrapie and the virus that causes foot-and-mouth disease (FMD), as both can devastate flocks.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] The latter poses a slight risk to humans.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] During the 2001 FMD pandemic in the UK, hundreds of sheep were culled and some rare British breeds were at risk of extinction due to this.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Of the 600,300 sheep lost to the US economy in 2004, 37.3% were lost to predators, while 26.5% were lost to some form of disease.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Poisoning accounted for 1.7% of non-productive deaths.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] When all else fails, vetrinarians can perform a necropsy on a dead sheep's carcass.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] While it is obviously too late to save that sheep, this can aid in understanding the cause of death, and if there is a broader threat to the flock.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Other than parasites and disease, predation is a threat to sheep and the profitability of sheep raising.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Sheep have little ability to defend themselves, compared with other species kept as livestock.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Even if sheep survive an attack, they may die from their injuries or simply from panic.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] However, the impact of predation varies dramatically with region.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] In Africa, Australia, the Americas, and parts of Europe and Asia predators are a serious problem.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] In the United States, for instance, over one third of sheep deaths in 2004 were caused by predation.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] In contrast, other nations are virtually devoid of sheep predators, particularly islands known for extensive sheep husbandry.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Worldwide, canids—including the domestic dog—are responsible for most sheep deaths.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Other animals that occasionally prey on sheep include: felines, bears, birds of prey, ravens and feral hogs.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Sheep producers have used a wide variety of measures to combat predation.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Pre-modern shepherds used their own presence, livestock guardian dogs, and protective structures such as barns and fencing.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Fencing (both regular and electric), penning sheep at night, and lambing indoors all continue to be widely used.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] More modern shepherds used guns, traps, and poisons to kill predators, causing significant decreases in predator populations.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] In the wake of the environmental and conservation movements, the use of these methods now usually falls under the purview of specially designated government agencies in most developed countries.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] The 1970s saw a resurgence in the use of livestock guardian dogs and the development of new methods of predator control by sheep producers, many of them non-lethal.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Donkeys and guard llamas have been used since the 1980s in sheep operations, using the same basic principle as livestock guardian dogs.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Interspecific pasturing, usually with larger livestock such as cattle or horses, may help to deter predators, even if such species do not actively guard sheep.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] In addition to animal guardians, contemporary sheep operations may use non-lethal predator deterrents such as motion-activated lights and noisy alarms.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Sheep are an important part of the global agricultural economy.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] While historically of top importance and relevance, their status has been eclipsed in the 20th century by other livestock species, especially the pig, chicken, and cow.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] China, Australia, India, Nigeria, and Iran have the largest modern flocks, and serve both local and exportation needs for wool and mutton.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Other countries such as New Zealand have smaller flocks but retain a large international economic impact due to their export of sheep products.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Sheep also play a role in local economies, such as niche markets focused on organic or sustainable agriculture and local food customers.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Especially in developing countries, such flocks may be a part of subsistence agriculture rather than a system of trade.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Sheep themselves may be a medium of trade in barter economies.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Domestic sheep provide a wide array of raw materials.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Wool was one of the first textiles and historically important for millennia.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] In the late 20th century, wool prices began to fall dramatically.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] This was the result of the popularity and cheap prices for synthetic fabrics reducing demand, as well as a growth in the size of flocks in China that supplied wool at low cost.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] For some sheep owners, the cost of shearing is greater than the profit from the fleece.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Fleeces are used as material in making products such as wool insulation for buildings.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] In the 21st century, the sale of lamb and mutton meat is the most profitable enterprise in the sheep industry, although less sheep meat is consumed than chicken, pork, or beef.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Sheepskin is likewise used for making clothes, footwear, rugs, and other products.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Byproducts from the slaughter of sheep are also of value: sheep tallow can be used in candle and soap making, sheep bone and cartilage has been used to furnish carved items such as dice and buttons as well as rendered glue and gelatin.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Sheep intestines can be formed into sausage.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] The intestine casing (wall), especially of lambs, has historically been used as catgut for surgical sutures, for stringing tennis rackets, and as strings for musical string instruments.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Sheep droppings, which are high in cellulose, have even been sterilized and mixed with traditional pulp materials to make paper.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Lanolin, the waterproof, fatty substance found naturally in sheep's wool, is used as a base for cosmetics and as a lubricant in other products.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Some farmers who keep sheep also make a profit from live sheep.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Providing lambs for youth programs such as 4-H and competition at agricultural shows is one option.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Farmers may also choose to focus on a particular breed of sheep in order to sell registered purebred animals, as well as provide a ram rental service for breeding.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] A more recent option for deriving profit from live sheep is the rental of flocks for grazing; these "mowing services" are hired in order to remove unwanted vegetation from public spaces and to lessen fire hazard.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Despite the falling demand and price for sheep products in many markets, sheep have distinct economic advantages when compared with other livestock.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] They do not require expensive housing, such as that used in the intensive farming of chickens or pigs.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] They are an efficient use of land; roughly six sheep can be kept on the amount that would suffice for a single cow or horse.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Sheep can also consume plants, such as noxious weeds, that most other animals will not touch, and produce more young at a faster rate.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] In contrast to most livestock species, the cost of raising sheep is not necessarily tied to the price of feed crops such as grain, soybeans and corn.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Combined with the lower cost of quality sheep, all these factors combine to equal a lower overhead for sheep producers, thus entailing a higher profitability potential for the small farmer.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Sheep are especially beneficial for independent producers, including family farms with limited resources, as the sheep industry is one of the few types of animal agriculture that has not been vertically integrated by agribusiness.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] However, small flocks, from 10 to 50 ewes, often are not profitable because they tend to be poorly managed.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] The primary reason is that mechanization is not feasible, so return per hour of labor is not maximized.
[src:sheep/sheep-p01] Small farm flocks generally are used simply to control weeds on irrigation ditches or maintained as a hobby.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] Sheep meat and milk were one of the earliest staple proteins consumed by human civilization after the transition from hunting and gathering to agriculture.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] Sheep meat prepared for food is known as either mutton or lamb, and approximately 540 million sheep are slaughtered each year for meat worldwide.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] "Mutton" is derived from the Old French *moton*, which was the word for sheep used by the Anglo-Norman rulers of much of the British Isles in the Middle Ages.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] This became the name for sheep meat in English, while the Old English word *sceap* was kept for the live animal.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] Throughout modern history, "mutton" has been limited to the meat of mature sheep usually at least two years of age; "lamb" is used for that of immature sheep less than a year.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] In the 21st century, the nations with the highest consumption of sheep meat are the Arab states of the Persian Gulf, New Zealand, Australia, Greece, Uruguay, the United Kingdom and Ireland.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] These countries eat 14–40 lbs (3–18 kg) of sheep meat *per capita*, *per annum*.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] Sheep meat is also popular in France, Africa (especially the Arab world), the Caribbean, the rest of the Middle East, India, and parts of China.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] This often reflects a history of sheep production.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] In these countries in particular, dishes comprising alternative cuts and offal may be popular or traditional.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] Sheep testicles—called animelles or lamb fries—are considered a delicacy in many parts of the world.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] An unusual dish of sheep meat is the Scottish haggis, composed of various sheep innards cooked along with oatmeal and chopped onions inside its stomach.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] In comparison, countries such as the U.S. consume only a pound or less (under 0.5 kg), with Americans eating 50 pounds (22 kg) of pork and 65 pounds (29 kg) of beef.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] In addition, such countries rarely eat mutton, and may favor the more expensive cuts of lamb: mostly lamb chops and leg of lamb.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] Though sheep's milk may be drunk rarely in fresh form, today it is used predominantly in cheese and yogurt making.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] Sheep have only two teats, and produce a far smaller volume of milk than cows.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] However, as sheep's milk contains far more fat, solids, and minerals than cow's milk, it is ideal for the cheese-making process.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] It also resists contamination during cooling better because of its much higher calcium content.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] Well-known cheeses made from sheep milk include the feta of Bulgaria and Greece, Roquefort of France, Manchego from Spain, the *pecorino romano* (the Italian word for "sheep" is *pecore*) and *ricotta* of Italy.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] Yogurts, especially some forms of strained yogurt, may also be made from sheep milk.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] Many of these products are now often made with cow's milk, especially when produced outside their country of origin.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] Sheep milk contains 4.8% lactose, which is relevant for the lactose intolerant.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] As with other domestic animals, the meat of uncastrated males is inferior in quality, especially as they grow.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] A "bucky" lamb is a lamb which was not castrated early enough, or which was castrated improperly (resulting in one testicle being retained).
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] Sheep are generally too large and reproduce too slowly to make ideal research subjects, and thus are not a common model organism.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] They have, however, played an influential role in some fields of science.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] In particular, the Roslin Institute of Edinburgh, Scotland used sheep for genetics research that produced groundbreaking results.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] In 1995, two ewes named Megan and Morag were the first mammals cloned from differentiated cells, also referred to as gynomerogony.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] A year later, a Finnish Dorset sheep named Dolly, dubbed "the world's most famous sheep" in *Scientific American*, was the first mammal to be cloned from an adult somatic cell.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] Following this, Polly and Molly were the first mammals to be simultaneously cloned and transgenic.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] The sheep genome was sequenced in 2014, and a detailed genetic map was published earlier.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] In 2012, a transgenic sheep named "Peng Peng" was cloned by Chinese scientists, who spliced his genes with that of a roundworm (C. elegans) in order to increase production of fats healthier for human consumption.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] In the study of natural selection, the population of Soay sheep that remain on the island of Hirta have been used to explore the relation of body size and coloration to reproductive success.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] Soay sheep come in several colors, and researchers investigated why the larger, darker sheep were in decline; this occurrence contradicted the rule of thumb that larger members of a population tend to be more successful reproductively.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] The feral Soays on Hirta are especially useful subjects because they are isolated.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] Domestic sheep are sometimes used in medical research, particularly for researching cardiovascular physiology, in areas such as hypertension and heart failure.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] Pregnant sheep are also a useful model for human pregnancy, and have been used to investigate the effects on fetal development of malnutrition and hypoxia.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] In behavioral sciences, sheep have been used in isolated cases for the study of facial recognition, as their mental process of recognition is qualitatively similar to humans.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] Sheep have had a strong presence in many cultures, especially in areas where they form the most common type of livestock.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] In the English language, to call someone a sheep or ovine may allude that they are timid and easily led.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] In contradiction to this image, male sheep are often used as symbols of virility and power; the logos of the Los Angeles Rams football team and the Dodge Ram pickup truck allude to males of the bighorn sheep, *Ovis canadensis*.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] Counting sheep is popularly said to be an aid to sleep, and some ancient systems of counting sheep persist today.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] Sheep also enter in colloquial sayings and idiom frequently with such phrases as "black sheep".
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] To call an individual a black sheep implies that they are an odd or disreputable member of a group.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] This usage derives from the recessive trait that causes an occasional black lamb to be born into an entirely white flock.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] These black sheep were considered undesirable by shepherds, as black wool is not as commercially viable as white wool.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] Citizens who accept overbearing governments have been referred to by the Portmanteau neologism of sheeple.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] Somewhat differently, the adjective "sheepish" is also used to describe embarrassment.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] In British heraldry, sheep appear in the form of rams, sheep proper and lambs.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] These are distinguished by the ram being depicted with horns and a tail, the sheep with neither and the lamb with its tail only.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] A further variant of the lamb, termed the Paschal lamb, is depicted as carrying a Christian cross and with a halo over its head.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] Rams' heads, portrayed without a neck and facing the viewer, are also found in British armories.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] The fleece, depicted as an entire sheepskin carried by a ring around its midsection, originally became known through its use in the arms of the Order of the Golden Fleece and was later adopted by towns and individuals with connections to the wool industry.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] In Australian English slang, "on the sheep's back" is a phrase used to allude to wool as the source of Australia’s national prosperity.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] In antiquity, symbolism involving sheep cropped up in religions in the ancient Near East, the Mideast, and the Mediterranean area: Çatalhöyük, ancient Egyptian religion, the Cana'anite and Phoenician tradition, Judaism, Greek religion, and others.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] Religious symbolism and ritual involving sheep began with some of the first known faiths: Skulls of rams (along with bulls) occupied central placement in shrines at the Çatalhöyük settlement around 6,000 BCE.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] In Ancient Egyptian religion, the ram was the symbol of several gods: Khnum, Heryshaf and Amun (in his incarnation as a god of fertility).
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] Other deities occasionally shown with ram features include the goddess Ishtar, the Phoenician god Baal-Hamon, and the Babylonian god Ea-Oannes.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] In Madagascar, sheep were not eaten as they were believed to be incarnations of the souls of ancestors.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] There are many ancient Greek references to sheep: that of Chrysomallos, the golden-fleeced ram, continuing to be told through into the modern era.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] Astrologically, Aries, the ram, is the first sign of the classical Greek zodiac, and the sheep is the eighth of the twelve animals associated with the 12-year cycle of the Chinese zodiac, related to the Chinese calendar.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] Sheep play an important role in all the Abrahamic faiths; Abraham, Isaac, Jacob, Moses, and King David were all shepherds.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] According to the Biblical story of the Binding of Isaac, a ram is sacrificed as a substitute for Isaac after an angel stays Abraham's hand (in the Islamic tradition, Abraham was about to sacrifice Ishmael).
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] Eid al-Adha is a major annual festival in Islam in which sheep (or other animals) are sacrificed in remembrance of this act.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] Sheep are occasionally sacrificed to commemorate important secular events in Islamic cultures.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] Greeks and Romans sacrificed sheep regularly in religious practice, and Judaism once sacrificed sheep as a Korban (sacrifice), such as the Passover lamb.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] Ovine symbols—such as the ceremonial blowing of a shofar—still find a presence in modern Judaic traditions.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] Collectively, followers of Christianity are often referred to as a flock, with Christ as the Good Shepherd, and sheep are an element in the Christian iconography of the birth of Jesus.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] Some Christian saints are considered patrons of shepherds, and even of sheep themselves.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] Christ is also portrayed as the Sacrificial lamb of God (*Agnus Dei*) and Easter celebrations in Greece and Romania traditionally feature a meal of Paschal lamb.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] A church leader is often called the pastor, which is derived from the Latin word for shepherd.
[src:sheep/sheep-p02] In many western Christian traditions bishops carry a staff, which also serves as a symbol of the episcopal office, known as a crosier, modeled on the shepherd's crook.
